/// data : [{"ID":"4103","post_author":"3","post_title":"Douglas (Doug) Lee Williams","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[4109,4106]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams5.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"4109\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams5.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=4109\" class=\"wp-image-4109\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams8.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"4106\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams8.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=4106\" class=\"wp-image-4106\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born August 9, 1955</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Football Player</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":4104} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/Doug-Williams.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Late January is the time of year when in the United States, our version of football tends to take over the national consciousness. Around this time, the NFL playoffs and coming of the Super Bowl enter the forefront of our minds. Not so much in recent years, but in the late 80s there were very few black quarterbacks in the NFL, and there was an undercurrent sense that black athletes did not possess the leadership qualities and instincts that it took to be successful in that position. Well, on this day, January 31, 1988, all of that thinking changed, thanks to one man, our brother Doug Williams. This is his triumphant story of victory. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4110,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4110\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Douglas “Doug” Lee Williams attended Grambling State University where he played under our brother, head coach Eddie Robinson. As quarterback, Doug guided the Tigers to a 36–7 (.837 winning percentage) record as a four-year starter, and led the Tigers to three conference championships.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1977, Doug Williams led the NCAA in several passing categories, including total yards from scrimmage, passing yards, and touchdown passes. Doug Williams finished fourth in the Heisman Trophy voting. Doug Williams graduated from Grambling with a bachelor's degree in education, and he began work on his master's degree before the 1978 NFL Draft.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite the success that he enjoyed on the field, a coach from the Tampa Bay Buccaneers (HOF coach Joe Gibbs) was the only NFL coach that visited him for scouting purposes. Impressed by his poise, work ethic, and studious nature, the coach rated Williams as the best quarterback in the draft and recommended that the Buccaneers select Williams with their first-round draft choice.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4108,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams6.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4108\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Following the recommendation of Gibbs, Tampa Bay drafted Williams in the first round (17th overall) of the 1978 NFL Draft. Williams became the first black quarterback taken in the first round of an NFL draft. His first preseason pass drew a standing ovation from the Tampa Stadium crowd. In a 1979 game against the Chicago Bears, Doug Williams and our brother, Bears quarterback Vince Evans made history by making it the first NFL game ever to have a black starting quarterback on both teams.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tampa Bay, which had won just two games in the first two years of the franchise, went to the playoffs three times in five seasons with Williams as starter and played in the 1979 NFC Championship game. During his time in Tampa Bay, Williams improved his completion percentage each season.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Williams was the only starting black quarterback in the NFL at that time. During his tenure with the Buccaneers, Williams was paid the lowest salary for a starting quarterback in the league, and less than the salary of 12 backups. After the 1982 season, Williams asked for a $600,000 contract. The Tampa Bay Bucs owner refused to budge from his initial offer despite the head coach’s endorsement.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4107,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams7.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4107\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Feeling disrespected by not being paid properly according to his merit, Doug Williams bolted to the upstart United States Football League's (USFL) Oklahoma Outlaws. The next season the Bucs went 2–14, and did not make the playoffs again until the 1997 season 14 years later. Over time, Tampa Bay’s willingness to let Doug Williams walk away over such a relatively small amount of money was seen as insensitive, especially as it came only months after Doug Williams’ wife passed away suddenly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1984, Williams led the Outlaws of the USFL in passing, however, after the USFL was shut down in 1986, Doug Williams returned to the NFL, joining the Washington Redskins. He was reunited with his former offensive coordinator, Joe Gibbs, who was now the team's head coach. Initially, Williams served as the backup for the starting quarterback, but after the starter became injured, Doug Williams stepped in and led the Redskins to an opening-day victory against the Philadelphia Eagles in the 1987 season.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4112,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4112\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Doug Williams would start three times in the 1987 regular season. While the subsequent two starts were losses, at the end of the season, when the Redskins had qualified for the playoffs, Williams was chosen as the starter. And on this day, January 31, 1988, before an international audience, he bravely led the team to Super Bowl XXII in which they routed John Elway and the Denver Broncos, becoming the first black quarterback to both play in and win a Super Bowl. He threw for a record (at the time) of 340 yards (and four touchdowns), and he was named the Most Valuable Player of the championship game.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4111,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams3-770x1024.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4111\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He suffered from injuries the following season and was outplayed by the bench player, who eventually won the starting job from Williams. Doug Williams would play one final season in 1989, as a backup.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Following his departure from the NFL, Williams worked on television in 1990 as a college football analyst for the Black Entertainment Television (BET).&nbsp;&nbsp;Despite enjoying the change of pace, Williams longed to return to football and when a high school head coaching position opened up in 1991 at a new high School in Louisiana, Doug Williams applied for the job and was hired for the position.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1992, Williams was able to move on to coach to his former high school. Playing its home games on a field bearing his name, Doug Williams was able to lead the team to an undefeated regular season.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Williams moved to the collegiate coaching ranks in 1994, when he was hired as the running backs coach for the football team of the United States Naval Academy. His other jobs in football have also included work as an offensive coordinator and as a scout.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Doug Williams began his collegiate head coaching career at Morehouse College in 1997. He was named the head football coach at Grambling State University the following year, succeeding the legendary Eddie Robinson. He led the Tigers to three consecutive conference titles from 2000–2002, before leaving to rejoin the Tampa Bay Buccaneers as a personnel executive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4105,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams9.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4105\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2009, Doug Williams and fellow Grambling State alumnus James Harris co-founded the Black College Football Hall of Fame. Each year, several notable football players from historically black colleges and universities are entered in its hall of fame at an induction ceremony in Atlanta.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2022-01-31 06:37:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"41085","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"4028","post_author":"3","post_title":"Bob Johnson and the Story of BET","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4033,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson6.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4033\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born April 8, 1946&nbsp;| January 25, 1980</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>The Story of the Founder of Black Entertainment Television (BET)&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":4029} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/Bob-Johnson.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Robert “Bob” Louis Johnson was born in 1946 in Hickory, Mississippi, the ninth out of ten children. His mother was a teacher and his father was a farmer. His parents moved the family to Freeport, Illinois when he was a child. He was an honors student in high school. Bob Johnson graduated from the University of Illinois in 1968 with a bachelor's degree in social studies. He received a master's degree in public affairs from Princeton University in 1972.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After graduating from Princeton, Bob Johnson found a job in Washington, D.C., that introduced him to the television industry. He served as the public affairs director for the Corporation for Public Broadcasting. In this position is where he learned of the power and untapped potential of television. Around the same time, he also worked as the director of communications for the Washington, D.C. office of the National Urban League. Bob Johnson also worked as a press secretary for our brother, Congressman Walter E. Fauntroy. He later became vice president of government relations at the National Cable and Television Association (NCTA).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After stepping down as a lobbyist for the cable industry; and armed with the knowledge he learned from his experience, Bob Johnson decided to elevate his game and launch his own cable television network. Bob would soon acquire a loan for $15,000 and a $500,000 investment from media executive John Malone to start the network. The network, which was named&nbsp;<em><u>Black Entertainment Television</u></em>&nbsp;(BET), was launched on this day, January 25, 1980. The logo that would represent the network, featured a star to symbolize \"<em>Black Star Power</em>\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[4031]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-1 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson8.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"4031\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson8.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=4031\" class=\"wp-image-4031\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Initially, broadcasting for two hours a week as a block of programming on another network,&nbsp;<em><u>BET</u></em>’s programming comprised of music videos and reruns of popular black sitcoms.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It would not be until 1983 that&nbsp;<em><u>BET</u></em>&nbsp;became a full-fledged entity, independent of any other channel or programming block, though for years it continued to share channel space with other cable networks on local cable systems due to lack of channel room.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4030,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson9.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4030\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BET launched a news program,&nbsp;<em><u>BET News</u></em>, in 1988, with our brother, Ed Gordon as its anchor. In 1991, the network became the first black-controlled television company to be listed on the New York Stock Exchange. Starting the late 1990s, the network expanded with the expansion of the internet and the launch of digital cable networks.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2001, the network lost its status as a black-owned business when it was bought by media conglomerate Viacom for $3 billion. In 2005, Johnson retired from the network, turning over his titles of president and chief executive officer to former <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>BET</em></span> vice president Debra L. Lee. Bob Johnson earned over $1 billion from the sale, and thereby became America’s first black American billionaire.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[4038,4037]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"4038\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson1.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=4038\" class=\"wp-image-4038\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"4037\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson2.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=4037\" class=\"wp-image-4037\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In July 2017, Viacom signed new film and television development deals with our brother, Tyler Perry. As part of this deal, Perry would produce shows for <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>BET</em></span> and co-own the network's newly-launched streaming service, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>BET+</em></span>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4036,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4036\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After leaving BET, Bob Johnson founded&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">The RLJ Companies</span>, a holding company with a diverse portfolio including hotel real estate investment, private equity funds, financial services, automobile dealerships, and lottery gaming. The company is headquartered in Maryland.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bob Johnson became the first black majority club owner of a major American sports league team with his 2002 purchase of the&nbsp;<em><u>Charlotte Bobcats</u></em>. In 2010, Johnson sold his majority stake in the&nbsp;<em><u>Charlotte Bobcats</u></em>&nbsp;(re-branded now as the “<em><u>Charlotte Hornets</u></em>”) to our brother, the legendary Michael Jordan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4035,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4035\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bob Johnson stays ready in the business world as a member of the board of directors for several companies including his own, as well as large corporations like KB Home, Lowe's, the NBA’s Board of Governors, and the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of African American History and Culture.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4034,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4034\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the anniversary of BET, we salute your career Mr. Bob Louis Johnson. Thank you for your visionary leadership in providing an outlet for a countless number of artists and noteworthy individuals.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2022-01-25 06:31:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"44375","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BobJohnson7.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"3945","post_author":"3","post_title":"John Harold Johnson","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3961,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3961\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>January 19, 1918 – August 8, 2005</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Entrepreneur / Publisher / Tycoon</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":3946} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/John-Johnson.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you grew up black in America, in the pre-internet period, there is an almost 100% certainty that you came across a physical copy of an issue of <em><u>EBONY </u></em>and/or <em><u>Jet</u></em> magazine at least once in your lifetime. Before the internet, these magazines were a vital source of information, and they were pioneered by our brother John Harold Johnson, who started Johnson Publishing in the 1940s. This is his glorious story. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3963,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson7-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3963\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>John Harold Johnson was born on this day, January 19, 1918, in Arkansas City, Arkansas. His family moved to Chicago in the 1930’s during the period of time known as the “<em>Great Migration</em>” of black Americans out of the South.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Chicago, John Johnson endured a lot of teasing and taunting at his high school for his “country boy” ways. But being in Chicago exposed him to something he never knew existed: middle-class black people. John Johnson later transferred to a different high school for his junior and senior years. His classmates (at Jean Baptiste Pointe DuSable High School) included Nat “King” Cole and Redd Foxx.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Johnson's high-school career was distinguished by the leadership qualities he demonstrated as student council president and as editor of the school newspaper and class yearbook. He attended high school during the day and studied self-improvement books at night. After he graduated with honors in 1936, he was offered a tuition scholarship to the University of Chicago, but he thought he would have to decline it, because he could not figure out a way to pay for expenses other than tuition. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3954,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson9.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3954\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because of his achievements in high school, Johnson was invited to speak at a dinner held by the Urban League. When an attendee heard Johnson's speech, he was so impressed with the young man that he offered Johnson a job in his insurance company so that he would be able to use the scholarship.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Johnson began as a floater in the insurance office and within two years had become the assistant to the president. His duties included preparing a monthly digest of newspaper articles, for distribution to their company publisher. John Johnson began to wonder if other people in the black community might enjoy the same type of service. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3953,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson10.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3953\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He conceived of a publication patterned after&nbsp;<em><u>Reader's Digest</u></em>. His work at the insurance company also gave him the opportunity to see the day-to-day operations of a black-owned business and fostered his dream of starting a business of his own.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once the idea of <em><u>Negro Digest</u></em> occurred to him, it began to seem like a \"<em>black gold mine</em>\", Johnson stated in his autobiography (<em><u>Succeeding against the Odds</u></em>). He remained enthusiastic even though he was discouraged on all sides from doing so. Only his mother, supported his vision and allowed him to use her furniture as collateral for a $500 loan. He used this loan to publish the first edition of <em><u>Negro Digest</u></em> in 1942. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3951,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson12.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3951\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>John Johnson had a problem with distribution until he teamed up with a magazine distributor who was impressed with him. He provided valuable marketing tips to John and opened doors that allowed the new digest to reach newsstands in other urban centers. Within six months circulation had reached 50,000. The publication covered black history, literature, arts, and cultural issues. After several decades of publication its name was changed to <em><u>Black World</u></em>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Although&nbsp;<em><u>Negro Digest</u></em>&nbsp;achieved some success and at its height had a circulation of more than 100,000, it was dwarfed by Johnson's subsequent publication,&nbsp;<em><u>EBONY</u></em>, which was so popular that its initial run of 25,000 copies easily sold out.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The articles in <em><u>EBONY</u></em>, which were designed to look like popular magazines in the dominant society like <em><u>LIFE</u></em>, however emphasized the achievements of successful black Americans. Photo essays about current events and articles about race relations were also included in the magazine. Initially focused on the celebrities in the black community, John Johnson expanded the reporting to include matters such as social issues pertinent to black people. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3959,3958]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3959\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson4.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3959\" class=\"wp-image-3959\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson5.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3958\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson5.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3958\" class=\"wp-image-3958\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Professional historians were recruited for the magazine's staff. Black models were used in the magazine's advertisements and a conscious effort was made to portray positive aspects of black American life and culture. Everything in the magazine was addressed to the black consumer. John Johnson always maintained that&nbsp;<em><u>EBONY</u></em>′s success was due to the positive image of black Americans that it offered.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1951,&nbsp;<em><u>Jet</u></em>, a weekly news digest, began. In&nbsp;<em><u>Jet</u></em>'s first issue, John Johnson wrote, \"<em>In the world today everything is moving along at a faster clip. There is more news and far less time to read it</em>.\"&nbsp;<em><u>Jet</u></em>'s goal was to provide \"news coverage on happenings among Negroes all over the U.S.—in entertainment, politics, sports, social events as well as features on unusual personalities, places and events.\" Our brother, Redd Foxx called the magazine \"<em>the Negro bible.</em>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition to <em><u>EBONY</u></em> and <em><u>Jet</u></em>, other publications followed as well. In its 40th year of publication, <em><u>Ebony</u></em> magazine had a circulation of 2.3 million and was the primary reason that John Johnson was considered one of the 400 richest individuals in the United States. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3960,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3960\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition, <em><u>Johnson Publishing</u></em> owned Fashion Fair Cosmetics (the world's number one makeup and skin care company for women of color), and <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Supreme Beauty</span> products (hair care for men and women).  John Johnson was also involved in television production and produced the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Ebony Fashion Fair</span> (the world's largest traveling fashion show), which has donated over $47 million to charity. The show visited more than 200 cities in the United States, Canada and the Caribbean. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><u>Johnson Publishing</u></em> also has a book division which has employed more than 2,600 people, with sales of nearly $400 million. John Johnson also purchased three radio stations and served on the board of directors of several major businesses, including the Greyhound Corporation. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3950,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson13.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3950\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Johnson received numerous honors and awards for his achievements, including the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People's (NAACP) <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Spingarn Medal</span> in 1966 for his contributions in the area of race relations. In 1972, he was named \"<em>Publisher of the Year</em>\" by the major magazine publishers in the United States. He received a <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Candace Award</span> for Distinguished Service from the National Coalition of 100 Black Women in 1989.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1996, President Bill Clinton bestowed the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Presidential Medal of Freedom</span> on Johnson. In 1997, Johnson was inducted into the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Junior Achievement National Business Hall of Fame</span> and the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Arkansas Business Hall of Fame</span>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On August 8, 2005, our illustrious brother, John Harold Johnson made his transition due to congestive heart failure. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3949,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson14.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3949\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2010, the Noble Network of Charter Schools and Chicago Public Schools opened <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Johnson College Prep High School</span>, a public charter high school in Chicago Illinois' Englewood neighborhood in honor of Johnson and his wife Eunice. On January 31, 2012, the United States Postal Service honored John H. Johnson with a commemorative stamp as the newest addition to its Black Heritage Series. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2022-01-19 06:16:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"67219","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/JohnJohnson16.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"3596","post_author":"3","post_title":"Arsenio Hall","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3605,3598]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3605\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio1.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3605\" class=\"wp-image-3605\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio8-698x1024.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3598\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio8.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3598\" class=\"wp-image-3598\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born February 12, 1956</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Actor / Comedian / Media Personality / Writer / Producer&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":3597} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio-Hall.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Arsenio Hall was born in Cleveland, Ohio, on February 12, 1956. He is the son of a preacher. Hall's parents separated when he was six years old. At age seven, he became interested performing magic tricks, and eventually built a business for himself performing at local birthday parties, weddings, and <em>bar mitzvahs</em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He attended Ohio University, and majored in communications, though he transferred and graduated from Kent State University. Though he started out in advertising, in 1979 he moved to Chicago, switched to stand-up comedy and was \"discovered\" at a comedy club by our sister, the singer Nancy Wilson. He got his first jobs in entertainment as an opening act for such musicians such as Aretha Franklin, Patti Labelle, Wayne Newton, and Tina Turner.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Throughout the ‘80s, Arsenio appeared on various comedy and musical shows, including <em><u>Solid Gold</u></em>, <em><u>Motown Revue</u></em>, and <em><u>The Half-Hour Comedy Hour</u></em>. He made his feature film debut in 1987 with <em><u>Amazon Women on the Moon</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And 1987 would be a watershed year for Arsenio. He would tap into what would become the platform for his most successful professional endeavor. He took over hosting duties from Joan Rivers on&nbsp;<em><u>The Late Show</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3607,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio11.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3607\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is how it happened, in 1986, the Fox network introduced The Late Show Starring Joan Rivers, to directly challenge&nbsp;<em><u>The Tonight Show</u></em>&nbsp;Starring Johnny Carson. After a moderate start, ratings for the show sagged. The relationship between Rivers and Fox executives soured, and she quit in 1987. Arsenio Hall was also chosen to host the show for its remainder, and his stint proved immensely memorable. His easygoing, and playful, yet edgy style was a hit with audiences. Based on that success, he was approached to host his own syndicated late night talk show.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Two years later,&nbsp;<em><u>The Arsenio Hall Show</u></em>&nbsp;was born. Arsenio’s deal included hosting and executive producing duties on the show, which was produced by Paramount and his own company,&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Arsenio Hall Productions</span>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3604,3602]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3604\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio2.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3604\" class=\"wp-image-3604\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3602\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio4.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3602\" class=\"wp-image-3602\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And on this day, January 3, 1989, Arsenio Hall, became the first black American host a nationally syndicated late night talk show. The Arsenio Hall Show was aimed primarily at the younger black audience. However, the show quickly appealed to people of all races and began to attract a wide variety of guests. It quickly became the “cool” place for entertainers to go to in order to reach the younger generation.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Around this time, his cross-over into the mainstream as a leading media personality was evident as he hosted the&nbsp;<em><u>MTV Video Music Awards</u></em>&nbsp;during the network’s “<em>Golden Era</em>” from 1988-1991. From January 1989 to May 1994, The Arsenio Hall Show was a showcase for black Hollywood, and a proving ground especially for younger black artists.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of Arsenio’s noteworthy distinctions is that he provided what was the first, and for a time, only, mainstream showcase for upcoming hip-hop artists, and for controversial guests like our brother, the Hon. Louis Farrakhan. Popular entertainers of all backgrounds that normally went overlooked by the mainstream media also found a home with Arsenio’s audience, and many became frequent guests.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3601,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3601\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the late 80s, his collaborations with our brother, Eddie Murphy, were legendary as he also appeared in two films with him: the box-office hit&nbsp;<em><u>Coming to America</u></em>&nbsp;(1988) and&nbsp;<em><u>Harlem Nights</u></em>&nbsp;(1989).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Arsenio Hall Show started a half-hour earlier than The Tonight Show, and booked a much younger, and more diverse group of artists than his established rival. Because of this, Arsenio Hall carved out a sizeable market segment during his tenure, and his ratings were at their highest point.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3600,3599]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio6.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3600\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio6.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3600\" class=\"wp-image-3600\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio7.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3599\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio7.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3599\" class=\"wp-image-3599\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, when Carson retired in 1992, there was some controversy over who would become his successor, and it ended up spawning not one, but two late-night talk shows to rival Arsenio’s, with both of them aimed at younger audiences. Though the ratings for his show would drop subsequently, the show still performed relatively well; nonetheless, he chose to walk away and take time off for himself.&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">The Arsenio Hall Show</span>&nbsp;aired its final episode in May of 1994.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Arsenio Hall received two NAACP Image awards in 1991. In 1993, he executive-produced the feature film&nbsp;<em><u>Bopha!</u></em>, a story about a South African family living in the apartheid era.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After three years away from the public eye, Arsenio Hall returned to television in 1997 with his short-lived sitcom entitled&nbsp;<em><u>Arsenio</u></em>. He later took on a supporting role in the TV series Martial Law (1998-99).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Arsenio hosted a revival of the TV talent show&nbsp;<em><u>Star Search</u></em>&nbsp;in the early 2000s. His popularity as a media personality was still evident during this time as he appeared as guest host on many shows. And in 2012, Arsenio demonstrated his business acumen on the celebrity edition of the popular reality show&nbsp;<em><u>The Apprentice</u></em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With his win on the show, and his rising recognition on many social media platforms, there was a renewed interest in seeing a return of&nbsp;The Arsenio Hall Show. Arsenio gave the public what they wanted and made a comeback to late-night television in the fall of 2013 with a reboot of the show.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It debuted to strong ratings initially, but it was unable to consistently attract enough viewers for a prolonged period. The challenges of the syndication deal were such that it placed the show on different channels and times across different networks, which made it tough to lure in the millennial generation used to real-time and on-demand TV viewing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2019, Arsenio returned to his stand-up comedy roots in&nbsp;<em><u>Smart &amp; Classy</u></em>, a concert film for the Netflix streaming service. He also collaborated again with our brother, Eddie Murphy, and reprised many of his roles for the sequel to the 1988 classic,&nbsp;<em><u>Coming 2 America</u></em> (2021).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3606,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Semi1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3606\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And on this day, the anniversary of the debut of&nbsp;<em><u>The Arsenio Hall Show</u></em>, we have to give it up for the living legend, the spiritual glue of modern black Hollywood and an unsung pioneer in hip-hop culture, our amazingly talented brother, the one and only Arsenioooooooooooooooo Hall!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2022-01-03 06:12:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"1","media_id":"39622","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Arsenio3.png","likes":"1","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"3360","post_author":"3","post_title":"Cabell \"Cab\" Calloway III","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3362,3368]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3362\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway1.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3362\" class=\"wp-image-3362\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3368\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3368\" class=\"wp-image-3368\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>December 25, 1907 – November 18, 1994</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Entertainer (Bandleader / Singer / Dancer / Actor / Author) / Cultural Icon </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":3361} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Cab-Calloway.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our brother, Cab Calloway became one of the most popular entertainers of the 1930s and '40s, during his 65-year career. He was the portrait of the image and style of the time period known as the “<em>Harlem Renaissance</em>.” This is his story.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Born Cabell Calloway III on December 25, 1907, in Rochester, New York. His mother was a Morgan State College graduate, teacher, and church organist. His father, Cabell Calloway Jr., graduated from Lincoln University in 1898, and worked as a lawyer and in real estate. The family moved to Baltimore, Maryland, when he was 11. Soon after, his father passed away and his mother remarried.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Young Cabell grew up in West Baltimore. He often skipped school to earn money by selling newspapers, shining shoes, and cooling down horses at the Pimlico racetrack where he developed an interest in racing and betting on horses. After he was caught playing dice on the church steps, his mother sent him to a reform school run by his uncle.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Calloway resumed hustling when he returned to Baltimore and worked as a caterer while he improved his studies in school. He began private vocal lessons in the early 20s and studied music throughout his formal schooling. Despite his parents' and teachers' disapproval of his interest in jazz, he began performing in nightclubs in Baltimore.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It should be noted that Cab Calloway was a standout athlete. He played on his high school basketball team, and in his senior year he started playing professional basketball with a team in the Negro Basketball League. After graduating from high school, he would later turn down an opportunity to play basketball for the famed <em>Harlem Globetrotters</em>, because he wanted to pursue a career in entertainment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1927, Cab Calloway joined his older sister, Blanche, on tour for the popular black musical revue&nbsp;<em><u>Plantation Days</u></em>. His sister became an accomplished bandleader before him, and he often attributed her as his inspiration for entering show business. Cab Calloway's mother wanted him to be a lawyer (like his father), so once the tour ended, he enrolled in college in Illinois, but he was more interested in singing and entertaining.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cab Calloway spent most of his nights in Chicago nightclubs, performing as a singer, drummer, and master of ceremonies (MC). One evening he had the pleasure of meeting, and performing with, our brother, Louis Armstrong, who taught him to sing in the “<em>scat</em>” style. He then left college to sing with a band.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1929, Cab Calloway relocated to New York to lead the band. They had one notable performance, but they soon later broke up. Louis Armstrong recommended Cab Calloway as a replacement singer in the musical revue <em><u>Connie's Hot Chocolates</u></em>. He established himself as a vocalist singing \"<em>Ain't Misbehavin'</em>\" by our brother, Fats Waller. While Calloway was performing in the revue, he impressed another band, who thereafter asked Cab Calloway to be their lead vocalist. The band would eventually be known as “<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Cab Calloway and his Orchestra</span>.” </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3364,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway6.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3364\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1930, Cab Calloway got a gig at Harlem's famed <em>Cotton Club</em>. Soon, the bandleader became a regular performer at the popular nightspot. Cab Calloway hit the big time with \"<em>Minnie the Moocher</em>\" (1931). The song became iconic, and he would go on to become the first black recording artist to sell at least one million copies from a single. The tune's famous call-and-response \"hi-de-hi-de-ho\" chorus (improvised when he couldn't recall a lyric), became Cab Calloway's signature phrase for the rest of his career.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cab Calloway’s popularity and talents in entertainment led him to crossover into movies as well. He was truly one of the most successful performers of his era. During the 1930s and 1940s, he appeared in such films as <em><u>The Big Broadcast</u></em>(1932), <em><u>The Singing Kid</u></em> (1936) and <em><u>Stormy Weather</u></em> (1943). In addition to music and film, Mr. Calloway influenced the public with books such as 1944's <em><u>The New Cab Calloway's Hepster's Dictionary: Language of Jive</u></em>, which offered definitions for terms in the 1930s and 40s vernacular like: \"<em>in the groove</em>\" and \"<em>zoot suit</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3367,3365]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3367\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3367\" class=\"wp-image-3367\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway5.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3365\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway5.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3365\" class=\"wp-image-3365\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Calloway and his Orchestra had successful tours in Canada, Europe and across the United States, traveling in private train cars when they visited the South in order to escape some of the hardships of segregation. With his appealing voice, spirited onstage moves and sparkling white tuxedos, Cab Calloway was the star attraction. We would be remiss to forget that his group's musical talent was just as impressive. True to the game, Cab Calloway paid his band members well (the salaries he offered were second only to Duke Ellington's). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3366,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3366\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1948, as the public had stopped flocking to big bands, Cab Calloway switched to working with a smaller, musical ensemble. Beginning in 1952, he spent two years in the cast of a revival of the musical <em><u>Porgy and Bess</u></em>. Calloway took other onstage roles over the years, including the male lead in a 1967 production of <em><u>Hello Dolly!</u></em>, whose all-Black cast also featured our sister, Pearl Bailey.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Later in life, Cab Calloway stayed active and re-introduced himself to a new generation. He shared his life story in an autobiography (<em><u>Of Minnie the Moocher and Me</u></em> in 1976). He made a celebrated cameo in the popular film <em><u>The Blues Brothers</u></em>. He also appeared on <em><u>Sesame Street</u></em>, and was featured alongside our sister, Ms. Janet Jackson, in the classic music video for her song \"<em>Alright</em>\" (1990). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1993, President Bill Clinton presented Cab Calloway with a <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">National Medal of the Arts</span>. Calloway's later years were spent in White Plains, New York, until he had a stroke in June 1994. His health began to decline thereafter and our flashy, stylish brother, Cab Calloway; the first black person to have a nationally syndicated radio program, made his transition in November of 1994. He was 86 years old.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-12-25 06:10:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"1","media_id":"26916","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/CabCalloway7.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"3217","post_author":"3","post_title":"Jamie Foxx (Eric Marlon Bishop)","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3222,3221]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3222\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3222\" class=\"wp-image-3222\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3221\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx4.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3221\" class=\"wp-image-3221\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born December 13, 1967</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Entertainer (Comedian / Actor / Recording Artist)&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":3224} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Jamie-Foxx.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Eric Marlon Bishop was born in Terrell, Texas, on this day, December 13, 1967. Shortly after his birth, young Eric was adopted and raised by his mother's grandparents. His grandmother was a domestic worker and nursery operator, and his grandfather worked in landscaping. He has often acknowledged his grandmother's influence in his life as one of the greatest reasons for his success.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Eric began playing the piano when he was five years old. He had a strict Baptist upbringing, and as a teenager he was a part-time pianist and choir leader at a local church. His natural talent for telling jokes was evident in elementary school, when his 3<sup>rd</sup>&nbsp;grade teacher would use him, as a class reward: with good behavior from his classmates, young Eric would get the chance to formally tell them jokes.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Eric Bishop attended Terrell High School, where he received top grades and played basketball and football. His ambition was to play for the Dallas Cowboys, and he set passing records as a quarterback. He also sang in a band called “<em>Leather and Lace</em>.” After completing high school, Eric received a college scholarship to a school in San Diego, where he studied musical and performing arts composition.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3223,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3223\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Leaving college, Eric moved to Los Angeles to pursue a career in comedy. Eric first told jokes at a comedy club's open mic night in 1989, after accepting a girlfriend's dare. When he noticed that female comedians were often called upon first to perform, he serendipitously created the stage name “<em>Jamie Foxx</em>,” feeling that it was a name ambiguous enough to prevent any biases from the crowd and clever enough to help him get on stage. It is worth noting that he chose his surname as a tribute to our brother, the legendary comedian Redd Foxx.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1991, he was hired as a regular cast member on the classic variety show&nbsp;<em><u>In Living Color</u></em>. He went on to become one of the most outstanding cast members during the show’s tenure on FOX. Jamie left In Living Color in 1994, but in 1996 he returned to television with&nbsp;<em><u>The Jamie Foxx Show</u></em>, playing a struggling actor who lives in a hotel owned by his aunt and uncle.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jamie Foxx also began professionally exploring his interest in music during the 1990s. On a Christmas episode of&nbsp;<em><u>In Living Color</u></em>, Jamie sang Donny Hathaway’s “<em>This Christmas</em>” over the closing credits and a public interest in his voice soon followed. In 1994, he released&nbsp;<em><u>Peep This</u></em>, an R&amp;B album, that reached No. 12 on the Billboard charts, led by the single “<em>Infatuation</em>.”&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3225,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx7.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3225\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By the time his TV show ended in 2001, Foxx was beginning to be viewed as a talented dramatic actor. This was due in large part to his performance in the sports drama&nbsp;<em><u>Any Given Sunday</u></em>&nbsp;(1999). Playing the fictional football star “<em>Willie Beamen</em>,” Jamie Foxx showed incredible range in his performance, and proved that his TV charisma was translatable on the big screen.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His next notable film role was in Michael Mann's&nbsp;<em><u>Ali</u></em>&nbsp;(2001), playing Muhammad Ali’s loquacious cornerman. He later earned praise for his performance opposite Tom Cruise in the thriller&nbsp;<em><u>Collateral</u></em>&nbsp;(2004), for which he received outstanding reviews and an Academy Award nomination for “<em>Best Supporting Actor</em>.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While&nbsp;<em><u>Collateral</u></em>&nbsp;was a critical and commercial hit, Jamie Foxx drew more attention later that year for his starring role as our brother, “<em>Ray Charles</em>” in the biopic&nbsp;<em><u>Ray</u></em>. Bringing the legendary musician to life on the big screen, Jamie Foxx earned “<em>Best Actor</em>” wins at both the Academy Awards and Golden Globes, cementing his place on the Hollywood A-list.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3220,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3220\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2006, he further solidified his spot among Hollywood’s elite by releasing a new album,&nbsp;<em><u>Unpredictable</u></em>. The recording reached the top of the charts. Around this time, he collaborated with our brother Kanye West for the nightclub banger “<em>Gold Digger</em>” where he sings the hook, doing his own signature “<em>Ray Charles</em>” impression.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Later that same year, Jamie Foxx co-starred in the film adaptation of the well-known Broadway play&nbsp;<em><u>Dreamgirls</u></em> (2006), with our sisters, Jennifer Hudson and Beyoncé. Thereafter, he appeared in a variety of films in a supporting role, but in late 2012 he burst back onto the big screen with a leading role in Quentin Tarantino's action western&nbsp;<em><u>Django Unchained</u></em>. He starred as “<em>Django</em>,” an enslaved person who becomes free and teams up with a bounty hunter to find his wife and face off against her plantation’s owner, who has her in captivity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jamie also returned to the recording studio to release his third album,&nbsp;<em><u>Intuition</u></em>, in 2008, which was a huge success. The album's single, \"<em>Blame It</em>,\" hit No. 1 on the Billboard Hip-Hop chart, and (several years later) is still a favorite on the dance floor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jamie continued to stay busy in the 2010s and beyond, reprising roles from previous films as well taking on a plethora of new challenges, playing the President of the United States (<em><u>White House Down</u></em>) and a Marvel supervillain (<em><u>The Amazing Spider-Man 2</u></em>), and acting in a children’s movie (<em><u>Annie</u></em>).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2018, Jamie Foxx appeared in a remake of <em><u>Robin Hood</u></em> as the title character's trusted friend, the moor  “<em>Little John</em>.” The following year, he delivered a strong performance in <em><u>Just Mercy</u></em>, based on the true story of a black man who was wrongfully convicted of murder.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Among Jamie’s numerous other noteworthy ventures include <em><u>The Foxxhole</u></em> (2007), a channel on Sirius Satellite Radio, featuring stand-up comedy and music, including much of his own material.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3218,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3218\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jamie Foxx, the triple threat, continues to stay active in entertainment. Most recently, he worked as a voice actor in the Disney animated film <em><u>Soul</u></em>, while also lending his voice to projects in years past like the <em><u>Rio</u></em> franchise. He is set to reprise his role as “<em>Electro</em>” in the Marvel Cinematic Universe (Spider-Man series), as well as to portray our brother, \"Iron\" Mike Tyson in a biopic. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition to his work in TV, film, and music, we would be remiss to fail to mention his extensive work in the genre of stand-up comedy. He has performed on the legendary platform&nbsp;<em><u>Def Comedy Jam</u>,</em>&nbsp;as well as in several of his own stand-up concert films on networks like HBO.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And on his birthday, we have to give it up to one of the modern-day living legends, a man who has tasted great success in every avenue of entertainment he has chosen to take his talents, the omnipresent, Mr. Jamie Foxx!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-12-13 06:37:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"25772","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JamieFoxx6.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"3126","post_author":"3","post_title":"Samuel “Sammy” George Davis, Jr.","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3134,3133]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr2-868x1024.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3134\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3134\" class=\"wp-image-3134\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr3-676x1024.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3133\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3133\" class=\"wp-image-3133\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>December 8, 1925 – May 16, 1990</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Entertainer (Singer / Dancer / Actor / Comedian) / Icon&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":3127} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Sammy-Davis-Jr.-.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Samuel George Davis, Jr. was born on this day, December 8, 1925, in Harlem, New York. As an infant, he was raised by his grandmother. Sammy Davis's parents split up when he was three and he went to live with his father, who was working as an entertainer in a dance troupe. When his father and adopted uncle went on tour, young Sammy was brought along, and after learning to tap dance the three began performing together. They would eventually be dubbed the&nbsp;<em><u>Will Mastin Trio</u></em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3137,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr10.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3137\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because of the group's nomadic lifestyle, Sammy Davis, Jr. never received a formal education, though his father did occasionally hire tutors while they were on the road. During their travels in the 1930s, the young Davis not only became an accomplished dancer but also a skilled singer, multi-instrumentalist and comedian and was soon the star of the show. Sammy Davis also made his first appearance in film during this time, dancing in the 1933 short film&nbsp;<em><u>Rufus Jones for President</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1943, at the height of World War II, Davis’s career was interrupted when he was drafted into the Army. During his service, he directly experienced horrendous racial prejudice that his father had previously protected him from.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He was constantly harassed and physically abused by white soldiers (he suffered a broken nose from an attack by a white soldier). But Sammy Davis eventually found refuge in an entertainment regiment, where he discovered that performing allowed him a certain measure of safety and he enjoyed the challenge of earning the respect of even his most difficult audience members.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After the war, Davis resumed his showbiz career. He continued to perform with the Will Mastin Trio as the star of the act and also struck out on his own, singing in nightclubs and recording records. His career began to rise to new heights in 1947 when the trio opened for Frank Sinatra (with whom Davis would remain a lifelong friend and collaborator) at the Capitol Theatre in New York. A tour followed, as did a performance that caught the ear of a record company, who signed Sammy Davis to a recording contract in 1954.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3130,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr6.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3130\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Later that year, while driving to Los Angeles for a soundtrack recording, Davis was seriously injured in a car accident. The accident resulted in his losing an eye, and he would use a glass eye for most of his life. His recuperation also gave him time for deep reflection. He converted to Judaism shortly thereafter, finding commonalities between the oppression experienced by black American and Jewish communities.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Davis’s injury did not slow his ascent. In 1955 his first two albums (<em><u>Starring Sammy Davis Jr</u></em>. and <em><u>Sammy Davis Jr. Sings Just for Lovers</u></em>) were released to both critical acclaim and commercial success, which in turn led to headlining performances in Las Vegas and New York as well as further appearances in films and on television shows. Around this time Davis made his Broadway debut as well, starring in the 1956 hit musical <em><u>Mr. Wonderful</u></em>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3129,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr7.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3129\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By 1960, Sammy Davis was a star in his own right. But he was also a member of the legendary \"<em>Rat Pack</em>,\" comprised of Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, Peter Lawford and Joey Bishop, the hard-partying superstars of the Las Vegas and Los Angeles nightclub scenes. Davis appeared with members of the pack in the films like <em><u>Ocean’s 11</u></em> (1960), as well as many others. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3136,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr9.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3136\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Davis was also a featured player in films outside of the pack and had many acclaimed film performances in the 1960s. During this time, our brother, the iconic performer also released a steady stream of albums. Sammy Davis was nominated for a \"<em>Record of the Year</em>\" Grammy for the song “<em>What Kind of Fool Am I?,</em>” which reached the Top 20 of the Billboard pop charts. He also continued working in theater and was nominated for a Tony Award in the 1964 musical&nbsp;<em><u>Golden Boy</u></em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition to being active on stage, in films, and in making music, the complete entertainer, Sammy Davis hosted his own television variety series, <em><u>The Sammy Davis Jr. Show</u></em> (1966). And years later, he played host again on a syndicated talk show called <em><u>Sammy and Company</u></em>, from 1975-77. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3131,3132]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr5.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3131\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr5.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3131\" class=\"wp-image-3131\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr4-684x1024.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3132\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr4.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3132\" class=\"wp-image-3132\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite what appeared to be a free-swinging playboy lifestyle, a lifetime of enduring racial prejudice led Sammy Davis to use his fame for political means. During the 1960s, he became active in the Civil Rights Movement, participating in the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">March on Washington</span> and refusing to perform at racially segregated nightclubs. In fact, he is credited with helping integrate popular tourist destinations like Las Vegas and Miami Beach. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Davis also challenged the bigotry of the era by marrying a white actress at a time when interracial marriages were forbidden by law in 31 states. (President John F. Kennedy, in fact, requested that the couple not appear at his inauguration so as not to anger white Southerners.)&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sammy Davis's popularity helped break the race barrier of the segregated entertainment industry. Some critics would say, however, that he had a complex relationship with the black community, as exemplified by the criticism he received after publicly supporting President Richard Nixon in 1972.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nonetheless, throughout the 1970s and ’80s, the multitalented Davis continued his prolific output. He maintained his musical career, releasing albums well into the late '70s and getting his first #1 chart hit with 1972’s “<em>Candy Man</em>.” Davis appeared in films such as 1981's&nbsp;<em><u>The Cannonball Run</u></em>, and 1989’s&nbsp;<em><u>Tap</u></em>, with our brother, Gregory Hines.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He was also a guest on a wide variety of television shows (including the&nbsp;<em><u>Tonight Show</u></em>,&nbsp;<em><u>The Carol Burnett Show</u></em>,&nbsp;<em><u>All in the Family</u></em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em><u>The Jeffersons</u></em>) as well as soap operas (<em><u>General Hospital</u></em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em><u>One Life to Live</u></em>). And Davis made another turn on Broadway during the summer of 1978 in&nbsp;<em><u>Stop the World - I Want to Get Off</u></em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But while his career continued during the late '80s, Sammy Davis’s health began to fade. Sammy was a heavy smoker, and in 1989 doctors discovered a tumor in his throat. The fall of that year he gave what would be his final performance, at the Harrah’s casino in Lake Tahoe.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Shortly thereafter, Davis underwent radiation therapy. Though the disease appeared to be in remission, it was later discovered to have returned. In May of 1990, Sammy Davis Jr. made his transition at his home in Beverly Hills, California, at the age of 64. A few months before his passing, he was honored by an array of his peers at a February television tribute.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our magnificently talented brother, Sammy Davis Jr. was awarded the Spingarn Medal by the NAACP. He was a recipient of the Kennedy Center Honors in 1987, and in 2001, he was posthumously awarded the Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-12-08 06:21:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"31317","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/SammyDavisJr1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"3084","post_author":"3","post_title":"Jay-Z (Shawn Corey Carter)","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3089,3087]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JayZ2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3089\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JayZ2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3089\" class=\"wp-image-3089\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JayZ4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3087\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JayZ4.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3087\" class=\"wp-image-3087\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born December 4, 1969</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Recording Artist / Songwriter / Business Executive / Entrepreneur </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":3085} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Jay-Z.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jay-Z was born Shawn Corey Carter on this day, December 4, 1969, in Brooklyn, New York. His father left the family when he was only 11 years old. Thereafter, young Shawn and his three siblings were raised by their mother in the rough climate of the Marcy Projects (located in Brooklyn).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During his adolescence, Shawn became attracted to street life and engaged in some underworld activity. He attended multiple high schools and was a classmate of our brother, the rap legend Christopher “<em>Biggie Smalls</em>” Wallace. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Shawn began rapping at a young age as an escape from the violence and poverty that surrounded him in the Marcy Projects. In 1989, he joined the artist Jaz-O — an older gentleman who served as a mentor — to record a song called \"<em>The Originators</em>,\" which garnered the pair an appearance on an episode of&nbsp;<em><u>Yo! MTV Raps</u></em>. It was at this point that Shawn embraced the nickname “<em>Jay-Z</em>,” which has three layers, (1) it is an homage to his friend Jaz-O, (2) a play on his childhood nickname “<em>Jazzy</em>,” and (3) a reference to the J/Z subway station near his Brooklyn home.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even with a stage name, Jay-Z remained relatively anonymous until he and two friends, Damon Dash and Kareem Burke, founded their own record label, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Roc-a-Fella Records</span>, in 1996. In June of that year, Jay-Z released his debut album, <em><u>Reasonable Doubt</u></em>. The album reached No. 23 on the Billboard charts, and it is considered a classic hip-hop album which established Jay-Z as an emerging star in music.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Two years later, Jay-Z achieved even broader success with the 1998 album&nbsp;<em><u>Vol. 2 ... Hard Knock Life</u></em>. The title track, which famously sampled its chorus from the Broadway musical&nbsp;<em><u>Annie</u></em>, became Jay-Z's most popular single to date. He scored a Grammy win for the album and another nomination for the single. This marked the beginning of a very successful period in which Jay-Z would become one of the biggest names in music.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From the late 90s to the early 2010s, Jay-Z released a slew of No. 1 albums and hit singles. Among them are albums like&nbsp;<em><u>The Blueprint</u></em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em><u>The Black Album</u></em>&nbsp;which are considered some of the best hip-hop records of all-time.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Very protective of his private life, for many years Jay-Z did not publicly discuss the relationship with his longtime girlfriend, the popular singer and actress, our sister Beyoncé Knowles. The couple even managed to keep the press away from their small wedding, which was held in April of 2008, in New York City. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3088,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JayZ3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3088\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was also during this period that Jay-Z turned his attention more to the business side of music, becoming President of Def Jam Recordings. As president of Def Jam, Jay-Z signed such popular acts as Rihanna, Ne-Yo, and helped Kanye West transition from producer to a best-selling recording artist. But his reign at the revered hip-hop label wasn't all smooth sailing; Jay-Z resigned as Def Jam's president in 2007, complaining about the company's resistance to change.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2008, Jay-Z signed a $150 million contract with the concert promotion company Live Nation. This super deal created a joint venture called <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Roc Nation</span>, an entertainment company that handles nearly all aspects of its artists' careers. Along with Jay-Z, Roc Nation signed such top artists as Rihanna, Shakira and T.I., among many others, to its roster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jay-Z's other business ventures include the popular clothing line <u>Rocawear</u> and <u>Roc-a-Fella Films</u>. He also owns the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">40/40 Club</span>, an upscale sports bar that opened in New York City with venues in other cities. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A part-owner of the New Jersey Nets basketball team since 2004, Jay-Z helped spur the relocation of the franchise to a brand-new home in downtown Brooklyn, the Barclays Center, in 2012. In 2013, he launched a full-service sports management company, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Roc Nation Sports</span>, and sold his Brooklyn Nets shares in order to pursue certification as a sports agent. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As Jay-Z once rapped about his business empire, \"<em>I'm not a businessman / I'm a business, man</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The business of Jay-Z made headlines once again in March 2015, when he and several of his high-powered friends, announced the relaunch of <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Tidal</span>, a streaming music service. The service gained a reasonable stream of followers, but also endured a significant amount of management and legal issues. In early 2017, Jay-Z agreed to sell his shares in Tidal to the telecommunications company, Sprint.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In June 2019, Forbes named Jay-Z the first billionaire rap artist, citing his ownership stakes in a champagne manufacturer and his early investment into the ride-share company, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Uber</span>, as contributing factors. Shortly afterward, he entered another burgeoning industry by becoming chief brand strategist of the California-based <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Caliva</span> cannabis company.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On June of 2017, Jay-Z became the first rapper to be inducted into the&nbsp;Songwriters Hall of Fame.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During this time, Jay-Z announced that he and his wife, Beyoncé, were teaming up for a tour that summer, and 10 days later, the couple gave their fans another reason to get excited with the release of a joint album,&nbsp;<em><u>Everything Is Love</u></em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In August 2019, Jay-Z and the National Football League announced a partnership in which Roc Nation would advise on entertainment selections for NFL promotional spots and events, including the Super Bowl. Additionally, the two sides agreed to work together on social activism efforts through the NFL's “<em>Inspire Change</em>” initiative.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The announcement was criticized by supporters of our brother, Colin Kaepernick, the quarterback who hadn't played in the NFL since protesting police brutality in 2016, but Mr. Carter expressed a belief that he could affect the social change sought by Kaepernick by working with the powerful sports league.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jay-Z was inducted into the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Rock &amp; Roll Hall of Fame</span> in October of 2021. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And on his birthday, we have to give our props to one of the best to ever do it, the man who successfully took hip-hop to the boardroom, our brother Mr. Shawn Carter, the man we all know as Jay-Z!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-12-04 06:51:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"15435","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/JayZ1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"3027","post_author":"3","post_title":"Gordon Roger Alexander Buchanan Parks","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3035,3034]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3035\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3035\" class=\"wp-image-3035\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3034\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3034\" class=\"wp-image-3034\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>November 30, 1912 – March 7, 2006</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Artist (Photojournalist / Film Director / Author / Poet)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":3028} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Gordon-Parks.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gordon Roger Alexander Buchanan Parks was born on this day, November 30, 1912, in Fort Scott, Kansas. His father was a vegetable farmer, and the family lived modestly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gordon Parks faced aggressive discrimination as a child. He attended a segregated elementary school and was not allowed to participate in activities at his high school because of his race. The teachers actively discouraged black students from seeking higher education. After the death of his mother when he was 14, Gordon left home. He lived with relatives for a short time before setting off on his own, taking whatever odd jobs he could find.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gordon Parks purchased his first camera at the age of 25 after viewing photographs of migrant workers in a magazine. His early fashion photographs caught the attention of Marva Louis, wife of our brother, “<em>The Brown Bomber</em>,” boxing champ Joe Louis, who encouraged Gordon Parks to move to a larger city. Gordon and his wife relocated to Chicago in 1940.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gordon Parks began to explore subjects beyond portraits and fashion photographs in Chicago. He became interested in the low-income Black neighborhoods of Chicago's South Side. In 1941, Parks won a photography fellowship with the Farm Security Administration (FSA) for his images of the inner city. Gordon Parks created some of his most enduring photographs during this fellowship, including \"<em>American Gothic, Washington, D.C.</em>,\" picturing a member of the FSA cleaning crew in front of an American flag.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3032,3031]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks5.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3032\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks5.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3032\" class=\"wp-image-3032\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks6.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3031\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks6.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3031\" class=\"wp-image-3031\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After the FSA disbanded, Parks continued to take photographs for the Office of War Information and <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">The Standard Oil Photography Project</span>. He also became a freelance photographer for <em><u>Vogue</u></em>. Parks worked for <em><u>Vogue</u></em> for a number of years, developing a distinctive style that emphasized the look of models and garments in motion, rather than in static poses.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Relocating to Harlem, Gordon Parks continued to document city images and characters while working in the fashion industry. His 1948 photographic essay on a Harlem gang leader won Gordon a position as a staff photographer for <em><u>LIFE</u></em> magazine, the nation's highest-circulation photographic publication. Gordon Parks held this position for 20 years, producing photographs on subjects including fashion, sports and entertainment as well as poverty and racial segregation. He also took portraits of black American leaders, like Malcolm X, Stokely Carmichael, and Muhammad Ali.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[3030,3029]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks7-694x1024.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3030\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks7.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3030\" class=\"wp-image-3030\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks8-684x1024.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"3029\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks8.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=3029\" class=\"wp-image-3029\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gordon Parks launched a writing career during this period, beginning with his 1962 autobiographical novel,&nbsp;<em><u>The Learning Tree</u></em>. He would publish a number of books throughout his lifetime, including a memoir, several works of fiction, and volumes on photographic technique.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1969, Gordon Parks became the first black American to direct a major Hollywood movie, the film adaptation of&nbsp;<em><u>The Learning Tree</u></em>. He wrote the screenplay and composed the score for the film.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gordon Parks’s next film, <em><u>Shaft</u></em>, was one of the biggest box-office hits of 1971. Starring our brother, Richard Roundtree as Detective “<em>John Shaft</em>,” the movie inspired a genre of films known as “<em>blaxploitation.</em>” (NOTE – <em>While the word “exploitation” is posited in the phrase, the film genre did not mistreat black entertainers, they were simply films, principally aimed toward black audience</em>s.) This film was monumental because, among other things, it introduced the concept of the black action hero into mainstream cinema.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our brother, Isaac Hayes won an Academy Award for the movie's theme song. Gordon Parks also directed a 1972 sequel, <em><u>Shaft's Big Score</u></em>. His attempt to deviate from the <em><u>Shaft</u></em> series, with the 1976 film <em><u>Leadbelly</u></em>, was commercially unsuccessful. Following this disappointment, Gordon continued to make films for television but did not return to Hollywood.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our brilliant and dynamic brother, Gordon Parks made his transition due to cancer in March of 2006, in New York City. He is buried in his hometown of Fort Scott, Kansas. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":3033,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3033\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Today, Gordon Parks is remembered for his pioneering work in the field of photography, which has been an inspiration to many. The works of Gordon Parks has been and continues to be exhibited in museums throughout the world. He has received over 20 honorary doctorates and a countless number of awards. In addition to his films, he has published over ten books of essays and photographs, as well as several books of poetry.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you, Mr. Gordon Parks, for your continued inspiration to generations of artists. Your legacy lives on in perpetuity.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-11-30 06:49:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"27288","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GordonParks1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2970","post_author":"3","post_title":"Bill “Bojangles” Robinson (Luther Robinson)","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2974,2973]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/BillRobinson3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2974\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/BillRobinson3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2974\" class=\"wp-image-2974\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/BillRobinson4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2973\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/BillRobinson4.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2973\" class=\"wp-image-2973\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>May 25, 1878 – November 25, 1949</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Entertainer / Actor / Dancer / Philanthropist&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2971} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Bill-Bojangles-Robinson-.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bill \"Bojangles\" Robinson started his career as a vaudeville performer and transitioned into one of the first major black entertainers of the modern era. His style and demeanor made him a favorite of both black and white audiences. This is his story.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bill \"Bojangles\" Robinson was born Luther Robinson in Richmond, Virginia, on May 25, 1878. His father worked in a machine shop, and his mother was a choir singer. After both of his parents died in 1885, Robinson was raised by his grandmother who had been an enslaved person earlier in her life.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to Mr. Robinson, he used physical force to compel his brother, Bill, to switch names with him, since he did not care for his given name of Luther (his brother eventually took on the name “Percy”). Additionally, as a young man, he earned the nickname \"<em>Bojangles</em>\" for his combative tendencies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the age of five, young Bill Robinson began dancing for a living, performing in local beer gardens. In 1886, at the age of nine, he joined a touring troupe. In 1891, he joined another traveling company, later performing as a vaudeville act. He achieved great success as a nightclub and musical-comedy performer. At this stage of his career, he performed almost exclusively in black theaters.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1908, Bill Robinson met a man who eventually became his manager. He urged Robinson to develop his solo act in nightclubs. Bill Robinson took a break from performance to serve as a rifleman in World War I. Along with fighting in the trenches, Bill Robinson was also a drum major who led the regimental band up Fifth Avenue upon the regiment's return from Europe.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1928, he starred on Broadway in the hugely successful musical revue&nbsp;<em><u>Blackbirds</u></em>&nbsp;of 1928, which featured his famous \"<em>stair dance</em>.\"&nbsp;<em><u>Blackbirds</u></em>&nbsp;was a revue starring black performers, intended for white audiences. The show was a breakthrough for Robinson. He became well known as \"<em>Bojangles</em>,\" which connoted a cheerful and happy-go-lucky demeanor for his white fans, despite the nearly polar-opposite meaning of the nickname in the black community.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2976,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/BillRobinson1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2976\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His catchphrase, \"<em>Everything's copacetic</em>,\" reinforced Robinson's sunny disposition. Although he worked regularly as an actor, Bill “Bojangles” Robinson was best known for his tap-dance routines. He pioneered a new form of tap, shifting from a flat-footed style to a light, swinging style that focused on elegant footwork.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Robinson's fame withstood the decline of black revue shows. His popularity allowed him to cross-over and star in 14 Hollywood motion pictures, many of them musicals, where he played multiple roles opposite the child-star Shirley Temple. His film credits include&nbsp;<em><u>Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm</u></em>,&nbsp;<em><u>The Little Colonel</u></em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em><u>Stormy Weather</u></em>, co-starring our sister, Lena Horne and our brother, Cab Calloway.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite his fame, Robinson was not able to transcend the narrow range of stereotypical roles written for black actors at the time. By accepting these roles, Robinson was able to maintain steady employment and remain in the public eye.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During his life, he came under heavy criticism for his seeming acceptance of racial stereotypes of the era, with some critics calling him an “<em>Uncle Tom</em>” (i.e. which, despite popular knowledge, is actually a reference to the “<em>Sambo</em>” character in the historic book&nbsp;<em><u>Uncle Tom’s Cabin</u></em>). He strongly resented this, and his biographers suggested that critics were underestimating the difficulties faced by black performers engaging with mainstream white culture at the time; and ignoring his many efforts to overcome racial prejudice.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In his public life (among other things) Bill Robinson led efforts to:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>persuade the Dallas Police Department to hire its first Black policeman,&nbsp;</li><li>lobby President Roosevelt during World War II for more equal treatment of Black soldiers, and&nbsp;</li><li>stage the first integrated public event in Miami, Florida.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bill “Bojangles” Robinson was also involved in baseball, as well as theater. In 1936, he co-founded the New York Black Yankees team, based in Harlem. The team was a part of the Negro National League until 1948, when Major League Baseball proceeded with racial integration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite earning millions during his lifetime, Robinson made his transition, financially destitute, on this day November 25, 1949, at the age of 71. However, his lack of tangible wealth was due to his personal philanthropy, as he donated much of it to charities in Harlem.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2972,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/BillRobinson5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2972\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bill Robinson's funeral, arranged by his longtime friend and television host Ed Sullivan, was attended by thousands, including many stars from the entertainment industry. A eulogy by Adam Clayton Powell Sr. (father of Congressman Adam Clayton Powell Jr.) was broadcast over the radio.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bill “Bojangles” Robinson remained a well-known figure after his death, particularly in dance circles. In 1989, a joint congressional resolution established <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">National Tap Dance Day</span> on May 25, Bill’s birthday. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, a public park in Harlem bears his name — a way of honoring his charity contributions and participation in the neighborhood's civic life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-11-25 06:01:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"17841","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/BillRobinson2.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2858","post_author":"3","post_title":"Whoopi Goldberg (Caryn Elaine Johnson)","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2861,2860]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2861\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2861\" class=\"wp-image-2861\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2860\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi1.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2860\" class=\"wp-image-2860\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born November 13, 1955</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Comedienne / Actress / Media Personality / Author </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2859} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi-Goldberg.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whoopi Goldberg was born Caryn Elaine Johnson on this day, November 13, 1955, in New York City. Young Caryn and her older brother were raised by their mother in a housing project in Manhattan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Caryn's father abandoned the family, and her single mother worked at a variety of jobs — including teaching and nursing — to make ends meet. She changed her name when she decided that her given name was too boring.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The inspiration for her stage name, \"<em>Whoopi</em>,\" came from the whoopee cushion comedic device. She says people would compare her personality to the feeling of a release of pressure. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In an interview she stated, “<em>People used to say to me, 'You're like a whoopee cushion.' And that's where the name came from</em>.\" Whoopi also says she has Jewish ancestry, and the name \"<em>Goldberg</em>\" is attributed to her family history.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whoopi Goldberg is best known for her skillful portrayals in both comedic and dramatic roles, as well as her groundbreaking work in Hollywood, as a black woman.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whoopi unknowingly suffered from dyslexia, which affected her studies and ultimately induced her to drop out of high school at the age of 17.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1974, she moved from New York to California, living in a variety of cities for the next seven years including Los Angeles, San Diego and San Francisco. At one point during this time, she worked as a mortuary beautician while pursuing her career in entertainment.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During her stay in San Francisco, Goldberg won a Bay Area Theatre Award for her portrayal of our sister, the comedienne “<em>Moms Mabley</em>” in a one-woman show.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Shortly after receiving this honor, she returned to New York City. In 1983, she starred in the enormously popular&nbsp;<em><u>The Spook Show</u></em>. The one-woman show featured her own original comedy material that profoundly addressed racial issues in America with unique style and wit.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By 1984, the show had moved to a Broadway stage, and in 1985, Goldberg won a Grammy Award for “<em>Best Comedy Album</em>” for the recording of skits taken from the show.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2864,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2864\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a result of this success, she began to receive significant attention from Hollywood insiders. Director Steven Spielberg cast Whoopi Goldberg in the leading female role of his 1985 production of&nbsp;<em><u>The Color Purple</u></em>&nbsp;(adapted from the novel by our sister, Alice Walker).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The film went on to earn ten Academy Awards and five Golden Globe nominations. Whoopi Goldberg received an Oscar nomination and her first Golden Globe Award, for \"<em>Best Actress</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whoopi's success with <em><u>The Color Purple</u></em> launched a highly visible acting career. Since 1985, she has appeared in more than 150 film and television productions. A recipient of numerous accolades, she is one of 16 entertainers to have the prestigious “EGAT” distinction. This merit signifies an elite inter-connection of excellence among the four major entertainment academies; for having won an <em><u>E</u></em>mmy Award (TV), a <em><u>G</u></em>rammy Award (music), an <em><u>A</u></em>cademy Award (film) and a <em><u>T</u></em>ony Award (theater; hence “<em>EGAT</em>”).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2863,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2863\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whoopi Goldberg's performance as the storefront psychic “<em>Oda Mae Brown</em>” in the 1990 film <em><u>Ghost</u></em> led to a number of milestone achievements. She won the Academy Award for \"<em>Best Supporting Actress</em>\" (1991), making her just the second black woman to win an Oscar. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1992, she starred in the enormously popular&nbsp;<em><u>Sister Act</u></em>&nbsp;as a past-her-prime lounge singer disguised as a nun for witness protection purposes. The film was a huge success and&nbsp;<em><u>Sister Act</u></em>&nbsp;earned Whoopi more accolades. The surprising success of the film led to&nbsp;<em><u>Sister Act 2: Back in the Habit</u></em>&nbsp;(1993), which featured many members of the original cast and the then-unknown R&amp;B artist, our sister, Lauryn Hill. Her salary for the role made her the highest-paid actress in Hollywood at the time.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2866,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi6.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2866\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over the years, her character became so iconic that in November 2019, Whoopi revealed that she would be reprising her role of “<em>Sister Mary Clarence/Deloris Van Cartier&nbsp;</em>” for a six-week run of&nbsp;<em><u>Sister Act: The Musical</u></em>&nbsp;in London.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whoopi has also made a name for herself as a TV-show Host. Beginning in 1986, she co-hosted&nbsp;<em><u>Comic Relief</u></em>, a live showcase of major comedians that annually raised money for the homeless. In 1997, she was given a special Emmy for her participation in the legendary HBO series. Also, Whoopi hosted&nbsp;<em><u>The Academy Awards</u></em>&nbsp;three times in the 1990s (1994, 1996 and 1999), making her the first woman to do so.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2002, she produced a Broadway show for which she received a Tony Award, and that same year won an Emmy for her starring role in the documentary&nbsp;<em><u>Beyond Tara: The Extraordinary Life of Hattie McDaniel</u></em>. In 2004, Whoopi returned to Broadway to star in her own self-titled one-woman show, and in 2006, she debuted a syndicated radio show,&nbsp;<em><u>Wake Up With Whoopi</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Her longtime familiarity with a variety of audiences continued to garner her more interest among Hollywood executives and in 2007, Whoopi Goldberg became the moderator of the daytime talk show&nbsp;<em><u>The View</u></em>. In 2009, she would share an Emmy win with her cast in the “<em>Outstanding Talk Show Host</em>” category.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whoopi Goldberg is also an author of both children's and adult books, and most recently, she dished out relationship advice with her 2015 book, entitled&nbsp;<em><u>If Someone Says 'You Complete Me,' Run!</u></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In March 2016, Whoopi Goldberg announced she was launching a cannabis brand aimed to help women with menstrual issues. The brand,&nbsp;<em><u>Whoopi and Maya</u></em>, is a collaboration with another named co-founder. Whoopi’s desire to get involved in the booming cannabis industry was due to her long-term experience with painful menstrual cycles. She's professed that cannabis was the only way she could find relief.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And on her birthday, this is real, it is no “<em>Act</em>,” we must give our “<em>Sister</em>” her flowers! Thank you, Ms. Whoopi Goldberg for your enormous contributions to the entertainment industry. Whether comedy, drama, or just straight conversation, your resume is truly legendary, and we are so grateful for your presence.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-11-13 06:01:54","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"20035","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Whoopi3.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2672","post_author":"3","post_title":"Aubrey Drake Graham","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2675,2676]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Drake2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2675\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Drake2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2675\" class=\"wp-image-2675\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Drake3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2676\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Drake3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2676\" class=\"wp-image-2676\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born October 24, 1986</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Recording Artist / Actor / Entrepreneur</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2673} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Drake.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Aubrey Drake Graham was born on this day, October 24, 1986, in Toronto, Canada. Drake grew up with music in his blood. His father was a drummer for the legendary rock star Jerry Lee Lewis. His uncle played bass for the funk band, Sly and the Family Stone.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Drake comes from a distinctive ethnic and religious background. His father is a black American Catholic and his mother is a white Canadian Jew. Speaking about his personal identity, Drake says: \"<em>At the end of the day, I consider myself a Black man because I'm more immersed in Black culture than any other. Being Jewish is kind of a cool twist. It makes me unique</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Drake's parents divorced when he was five years old, and he was raised by his mother in affluent and predominantly Jewish neighborhood in Toronto. He attended Jewish day school, had a Bar Mitzvah at age 13 and observed the Jewish High Holy Days. Despite his Jewish upbringing, Drake says he felt isolated at his virtually all-white school. He has said that \"<em>nobody understood what it was like to be Black and Jewish</em>,\" but added that \"<em>being different from everyone else just made me a lot stronger</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It was one of Drake's classmates at Forest Hill who gave him his start in the entertainment industry. One of his classmates’ father was an agent, whom suggested to his son that if he knew any classmates with talent, that he should connect them for an audition. Drake was successful in the audition and thereby secured artistic representation.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Shortly thereafter, in 2001, Drake landed a role on the Canadian teen drama series&nbsp;<em><u>Degrassi: The Next Generation</u></em>. The show followed the dramatic lives of a group of teenagers at Degrassi High School, and Drake played the part of “<em>Jimmy Brooks</em>,” a basketball star who becomes permanently wheelchair-bound when he is shot by a classmate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Drake dropped out of school to pursue his acting career. (he would eventually graduate in 2012). He starred on <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Degrassi</em></span> for seven years (2001-2009. The show quickly developed a devoted cult following propelling him to celebrity status in Canada, though he remained relatively anonymous in the United States.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While he was still appearing on <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Degrassi</em></span>, Drake began attempting to cross over into the world of hip-hop. He released his first mixtape, <em><u>Room for Improvement</u></em>, in 2006, achieving modest sales. He followed that with the 2007 release of another mixtape, <em><u>Comeback Season</u></em>, on his own <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">October’s Very Own</span> label (later to be shortened to OVO). This included Drake's first hit single and music video, \"<em>Replacement Girl</em>,\" which was featured as the New Joint of the Day on BET's popular hip-hop TV show 106 &amp; Park. More significantly, the song contained a version of the song \"<em>Man of the Year</em>,\" which featured Lil Wayne. Drake decided to leave Wayne’s verses and hook intact while he provided the rest of the lyrics himself. This caught the attention of Jas Prince, son of Rap-A-Lot Records founder James “J” Prince, who decided to play Drake to Lil Wayne himself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2008, the producers of <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Degrassi</em></span> overhauled the cast, eliminating Drake's character. Without his steady source of income, and not yet making significant money as a rapper, Drake was on the verge not making it further in the entertainment industry. But early in 2008, he received an unexpected call from our brother, Lil Wayne, who asked him to board a flight to Houston that night to join his <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">The Carter III Tour</span>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After touring and recording a number of songs with Lil Wayne, Drake released his third mixtape, <em><u>So Far Gone</u></em>, in February 2009. It featured the infectious single \"<em>Best I Ever Had</em>,\" which peaked at No. 2 on Billboard's Hot 100 singles chart. A bidding war for Drake’s signature followed and in mid-2009 he inked a record deal with Lil Wayne's, Young Money Entertainment. Since then, Drake's barrage of catchy, R&amp;B-infused hip-hop songs have dominated radio airwaves.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In June of 2010, Drake released his first full studio album,&nbsp;<em><u>Thank Me Later</u></em>, which debuted at No. 1 on both American and Canadian album charts and was certified platinum.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In November 2011, he released his second studio album,&nbsp;<em><u>Take Care</u></em>, which included the lead single \"<em>Headlines.</em>\" The album was universally acclaimed, winning the 2013 Grammy award for best rap album, among several other honors.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Although his career was flying high, Drake hit a few rough patches in his personal life. He has had public rivalries with several notable rappers including Chris Brown, Joe Budden, and Meek Mill.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, personal obstacles never seem to sidetrack Drake for long. His next two albums went on to receive critical acclaim and commercial success. This was evident in May 2017 when Drake was the big winner at the Billboard Music Awards. He took home 13 awards — including top artist, top male artist, top Billboard 100 album, breaking the record for the artist with the most wins in one year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His next album,&nbsp;<em><u>Scorpion</u></em>, somehow managed to top the success of his previous album. The album shattered streaming records over its first 24 hours, with a total of over 300 million streams on various music streaming platforms. The pace continued over the next several days, making Drake the first artist to top 1 billion streams in one week, with his studio release.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Drake has parlayed his celebrity into other business ventures outside of music. In 2013, Drake became the new \"<em>global ambassador</em>\" of the Toronto Raptors, joining the executive committee of the NBA franchise, while owning naming rights to its practice facility. In 2016, he began a line of bourbon whiskey (Virginia Black) that broke sales records in Canada. Drake has also designed fashion in collaboration with the famous apparel brand Nike. It was reported that in 2018, Drake was responsible for 5% of Toronto's total annual tourism income.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Among the world's best-selling music artists, with over 170 million records sold, Drake is ranked as the highest-certified digital singles artist in the United States. He has won four Grammy Awards, among several other music awards, and he holds several Billboard chart records.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In his relatively short career, our brother Drake has managed to become one of the most successful recording artists of all-time. We salute your example of consistency and craftsmanship, and we wish you all the best on your birthday!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-10-24 06:32:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"10698","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Drake1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2543","post_author":"3","post_title":"Richard (Dick) Claxton Gregory","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2546,2545]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/DickGregory2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2546\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/DickGregory2.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2546\" class=\"wp-image-2546\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/DickGregory1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2545\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/DickGregory1.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2545\" class=\"wp-image-2545\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>October 12, 1932 – August 19, 2017</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Comedian / Activist / Author</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2544} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Dick-Gregory.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Richard (Dick) Claxton Gregory was born on this day October 12, 1932, in St. Louis, Missouri. He was the second of six children. Dick Gregory grew up in crippling poverty. His father abandoned the family, leaving his mother to work long hours as a maid to support them. At an early age, young master Gregory found the power of comedy to defend himself against childhood bullies.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In high school, he became a track star and showed a thirst for activism when he protested against segregated schools. He was later accepted to Southern Illinois University where he excelled on the track field, and in 1954, he was drafted into the Army. He began performing stand-up comedy at this time, and after winning a talent contest, he became part of the Army's entertainment division.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After his return to the states, Dick Gregory worked as an emcee at various Chicago clubs, honing his craft working the comedy circuit while taking on odd jobs. His trailblazing style of satirical humor tackled racial issues and sociopolitical topics pulled straight from contemporary headlines.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gregory’s big break came in 1961 at Hugh Hefner’s Playboy Club in Chicago, where the comedian, as a replacement act, performed in front of a room of white executives visiting from the segregated South. Nonetheless, Gregory was a huge success and became a crossover star. In an interview, he said, “<em>It was the first time they had seen a black comic who was not bucking his eyes, wasn't dancing and singing and telling mother-in-law jokes.' [I was] just talking about what I read in the newspaper</em>.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dick Gregory had his run at the club extended by weeks and went on to become a national comedy headliner. That same year, Gregory made history when he appeared on&nbsp;<em><u>The Tonight Show</u></em>&nbsp;after making it clear he wanted to be invited to sit on the couch to chat with the host like mainstream entertainers, becoming the first black guest to do so. After his appearance, Gregory became a recurring guest on the show.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He also released popular albums&nbsp;<em><u>In Living Black and White</u></em>&nbsp;(1961) and&nbsp;<em><u>Dick Gregory Talks Turkey</u></em>&nbsp;(1962).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dick Gregory was at the forefront of the Civil Rights Movement during the 1960s and became friends with our brothers, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and Medgar Evers. He was arrested dozens of times because of his activism. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2549,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"className\":\"is-style-default\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-style-default\"><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/DickGregory5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2549\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He continued his political activism throughout the 1960s. In 1967, he unsuccessfully ran for the office of Mayor of Chicago. A year later, he also ran for U.S. President as a write-in candidate with the Freedom and Peace Party.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over the years, Gregory became devoted to health and fitness, adopting a vegetarian diet and examining issues related to diet within black communities. He became a noted university lecturer and also regularly went on hunger strikes to bring awareness to various global issues.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During the mid-1980s, Dick Gregory launched a weight-loss business known as the Slim/Safe Bahamian Diet. He eventually filed a lawsuit against his business partners and experienced major financial troubles that led to the loss of his family's farm.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He also turned away from stand-up for a time, but he later made his way back to performing. In 1996, he starred in the critically well-received theatrical production <em><u>Dick Gregory Live!</u></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2547,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"className\":\"is-style-rounded\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-style-rounded\"><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/DickGregory3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2547\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dick Gregory also authored a number of books, including&nbsp;<em><u>Nigger: An Autobiography</u></em>&nbsp;(1964). His other books include&nbsp;<em><u>No More Lies: The Myth and the Reality of American History</u></em>&nbsp;(1971),&nbsp;<em><u>Dick Gregory’s Natural Diet for Folks Who Eat: Cookin’ With Nature</u></em>&nbsp;(1973) and the memoir&nbsp;<em><u>Callus on My Soul</u></em>&nbsp;(2000).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1999, Gregory was diagnosed with lymphoma, but refused chemotherapy and instead turned to diet and alternative treatments. The cancer went into remission. Our magnificent brother, Dick Gregory, made his transition in August of 2017. He was dealing with complications from heart failure. He was 84 years old.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A documentary film about the life of Dick Gregory entitled <em><u>The One and Only Dick Gregory</u></em> made its world premiere at the Tribeca Film Festival in June of 2021, and was released to television the following month.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-10-12 06:45:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"15279","featured_media_src_url":"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/DickGregory4.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2528","post_author":"3","post_title":"Aida Overton Walker","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2531,2532]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2531\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker2.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2531\" class=\"wp-image-2531\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2532\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker3.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2532\" class=\"wp-image-2532\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>February 14, 1880 – October 11, 1914</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Entertainer (Vaudeville) / Choreographer&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2529} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Aida-Overton-Walker.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Aida Overton was born in Richmond, Virginia on February 14, 1880. Her family moved to New York City when she was young. There, she gained an education and considerable musical training.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At 5 years old, she joined a black touring group of performers. In the following years, she became a chorus member in “<em>Black Patti's Troubadours</em>,” this well-known group was headed by our sister, Sissieretta Jones, who became a famous soprano. In this group, she met her future husband, George Walker.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>George Walker was a member of a two-man comedy team (with Bert Williams) and Aida creatively fit right in with them and was featured in all of their landmark performances in the early 1900s. Her performance of “<em>Miss Hannah from Savannah</em>” in the show&nbsp;<em><u>Sons of Ham</u></em>&nbsp;created a national commotion. Furthermore, Aida did the all of the choreography for these shows and emerged as the glue that made the Walker-Williams shows work so well, as she worked behind the scenes with her husband supplying the themes and basic ideas for the shows, which then featured the great humor of Bert Williams.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Aida Overton and George Walker married soon after they began performing together. The trio became the major black vaudeville (and musical comedy) powerhouses of their time. For the next ten years, she was known primarily for her work in musical theater. Her song and dance routines made her an instant hit with audiences.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In these routines, Aida refused to play black plantation stereotypes and an essential part of her activism was to make the black woman stand tall and be an object of dignity and respect. She became a huge hit in England from 1902 to 1904 with&nbsp;<em><u>In Dahomey</u></em>&nbsp;and was frequently hired for private appearances because of the popularity of her dancing.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1904, after two touring seasons in England, the group returned to New York. She created a version of the “<em>Salome</em>” dance, which was a popular dance routine of the time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Working alongside her husband, Aida Walker's career and performances were praised by critics. Her successes were well-known. She was both financially successful and respected by the industry.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In late 1908, Aida's husband fell very ill and she left the stage for a time to care for him.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1910, Aida Overton Walker joined a different vaudeville company. During this time, she also began touring the circuit as a solo act. Her husband passed away in 1911.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After which she emerged as a female superstar and was often invited to prominent mainstream social gatherings to demonstrate her most recent choreography routines. She played the lead in Oscar Hammerstein’s 1912 revival of&nbsp;<em><u>Salome</u></em>&nbsp;at the Victoria Theater in New York. Her success at the theatre led to an invitation to return the following year. When she returned, Aida Walker's her performance was still so successful that she was asked to perform for an two extra weeks.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2534,2533]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker5.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2534\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker5.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2534\" class=\"wp-image-2534\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2533\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker4.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2533\" class=\"wp-image-2533\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She raised significant funds for the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Industrial Home for Colored Working Girls</span> and worked to promote opportunities for young black women in the entertainment business through her connections. She hoped to promote a new generation of refined and elegant black performers free of the demeaning stereotypes of the previous decades. To this end in 1913 and 1914 she promoted a troupe called “<em>The Happy Girls</em>” and produced shows for them to show black women as original creative talent. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our trailblazing sister, one of our first entertainment stars, Mrs. Aida Overton Walker made her transition suddenly from kidney failure in on this day, October 11, 1914. She had continued performing until only two months before her passing.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Her national and international recognition was such that she was a true legend of black entertainers. Her vision of a world of dignified black entertainers who did not have to demean themselves onstage was years ahead of reality.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She worked to help young black artists, and especially black women, become high-achievers through her own remarkable talents as a singer, dancer, actress, comedienne and choreographer. At the time of her passing, she was one of the most admired and respected black people in America.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thank you, Aida Overton Walker, for your incredible contributions to the culture!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-10-11 06:59:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"15189","featured_media_src_url":"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/AidaWalker1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2423","post_author":"3","post_title":"Dwayne Michael Carter, Jr. (Lil Wayne)","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2426,2427]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WeezyFBaby2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2426\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WeezyFBaby2.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2426\" class=\"wp-image-2426\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WeezyFBaby3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2427\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WeezyFBaby3.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2427\" class=\"wp-image-2427\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born September 27, 1982</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Recording Artist / Record Executive&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2424} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Lil-Wayne.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dwayne Michael Carter Jr. was born on this day, September 27, 1982, in New Orleans, Louisiana. His mother, a cook, gave birth to him when she was 19 years old. His parents divorced when he was two and his father permanently abandoned the family. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Wayne started rapping at the age of eight. He was enrolled in the gifted program in his elementary school. He was an honor student and a member of the drama club, playing the “<em>Tin Man</em>” in the school's production of <em><u>The Wiz</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1991, he met brothers Bryan and Slim Williams, the founders of Cash Money Records, who were impressed enough with his skills to give him one of their business cards. Ambitious, Wayne continued to call them until they took him under their wing and let him hang around the label's offices.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lil Wayne's first recording for Cash Money Records was&nbsp;<em><u>True Stories</u></em>&nbsp;(1993), he performed as a duo with another skilled New Orleans rapper, B.G., under the name “<em>The BGs</em>.” As part of “The Hot Boys,” Lil Wayne got his first taste of success. The group was made up of several of Cash Money's rising stars—B.G., Juvenile, Turk and Lil Wayne. Their debut album,&nbsp;<em><u>Get It How U Live!!</u></em>&nbsp;(1997), sold more than 400,000 copies. Their next effort,&nbsp;<em><u>Guerilla Warfare</u></em>&nbsp;(1999), did even better, eventually selling more than 1 million copies. At the age of 16, Lil Wayne was on his way to music stardom.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lil Wayne launched his solo career with&nbsp;<em><u>Tha Block Is Hot</u></em>&nbsp;(1999). The title track was a big hit, and the album reached the top of the hip-hop charts. The rapper's next two albums sold modestly compared to his debut. Then, in a career-changing move, Lil Wayne took a break from creating a traditional style album and released his first collection of underground mixtapes. This was in an era before modern day music streaming, and his mixtapes went on to become legendary in the streets.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the public hungry for more “Weezy,” in 2004, Lil Wayne released&nbsp;<em><u>Tha Carter</u></em>, a hugely popular album that helped cement his reputation as one of hip-hop's leading young artists. The single, \"<em>Go D.J.</em>\" did well on both the hip-hop and pop charts.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Quickly following up this latest wave of success, Wayne released&nbsp;<em><u>Tha Carter II</u></em>&nbsp;in December 2005. The album debuted at the No. 2 spot on the Billboard charts and brought more critical praise for Wayne.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over the next few years, Lil Wayne released several more popular mixtape recordings, while simultaneously releasing major label albums. In response to several unreleased tracks being made public over the internet, Lil Wayne released the download-only EP&nbsp;<em><u>The Leak</u></em>&nbsp;in 2007. The songs came from his work on his anxiously anticipated next studio album, which was finally released in 2008:<em><u>&nbsp;Tha Carter III</u></em>&nbsp;which made him the hottest rapper of the era, and even brought him mainstream attention. The album sold more than 1 million copies in its first week of release.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The project netted the Grammy Award for Best Rap Album, and Lil Wayne picked up three more Grammys at the awards ceremony in 2009. Lil Wayne released his seventh studio album, the rock-influenced&nbsp;<em><u>Rebirth</u></em>, in February 2010. His eighth studio project,&nbsp;<em><u>I Am Not a Human Being</u></em>, was released that same year. Both projects were a critical and financial success.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On top of the rap world, Lil Wayne around this time formed the rap supergroup “Young Money,” which among others, introducing the rap world to our brother, Drake and our sister, Nicki Minaj. He would continue to release popular albums throughout the early 2010s.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2015, Wayne was expected to release his eleventh studio album&nbsp;<em><u>Tha Carter V</u></em>, but he delayed the release of the album over disputes with the Cash Money label, instead dropping several mixtapes. After the rapper finally extracted himself from his Cash Money contract in June 2018, the long-awaited&nbsp;<em><u>Tha Carter V</u></em>&nbsp;debuted at the Billboard top spot in September. Wayne's thirteenth album,&nbsp;<em><u>Funeral</u></em>, was released in early 2020.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To date, Lil Wayne has sold over 120 million records worldwide, including more than 20 million albums and 70 million digital tracks in the United States, making him one of the world's best-selling music artists. He has won five Grammy Awards. And on this day, his birthday, September 27, in 2012, he became the first male artist to surpass Elvis Presley with the most entries on the Billboard Hot 100, with 109 songs.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lil Wayne also currently serves as the chief executive officer (CEO) of his own label,&nbsp;Young Money Entertainment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-09-27 06:15:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"9702","featured_media_src_url":"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WeezyFBaby1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2401","post_author":"3","post_title":"Willard (Will) Carroll Smith, Jr.","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2403,2402]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WillSmith3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2403\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WillSmith3.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2403\" class=\"wp-image-2403\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WillSmith4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2402\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WillSmith4.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2402\" class=\"wp-image-2402\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born September 25, 1968</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Recording Artist / Actor / Producer&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2407} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Will-Smith.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Willard Carroll Smith, Jr. was born on this day, September 25, 1968, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. His mother worked for the school board, and his father owned a refrigeration company.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His West Philadelphia neighborhood was a melting pot of cultures. Will was a good student whose charming personality and fast-talking were renowned for getting him out of trouble, a trait for which he soon gained the nickname \"<em>Prince</em>.''</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Smith began rapping at age 12, emulating the rap pioneers of the day, but lacing his rhymes with a comedic element that would later become his trademark. At age 16, Will Smith met our brother, and future collaborator Jeff Townes at a party. The pair became friends, and the duo&nbsp;<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">DJ Jazzy Jeff &amp; The Fresh Prince</span>&nbsp;was born.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As teens, DJ Jazzy Jeff &amp; The Fresh Prince began producing music but steered clear of the more adult, street sound that was emerging at the time. The Fresh Prince rapped about teenage preoccupations in a clean, curse-free style that many found safe and entertaining. The pair's first single, \"<em>Girls Ain't Nothing But Trouble</em>,\" was a hit in 1986. Their 1987 debut album,&nbsp;<em><u>Rock the House</u></em>, hit the Billboard Top 200, and made Will Smith a millionaire before the age of 18.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1988, DJ Jazzy Jeff &amp; The Fresh Prince continued their success with the album&nbsp;<em><u>He's The DJ, I'm The Rapper</u></em>. Featuring the radio-friendly single \"<em>Parents Just Don't Understand</em>,\" the album won the first-ever Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance. It was followed in 1989 with another album, which continued the pair's rise to stardom.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Two years later, Smith began his crossover into acting. Drawing on his experiences with fledgling stardom, NBC signed Smith to headline a sitcom about a street-smart kid from Philadelphia who moves in with stuffy relatives in the high-class Los Angeles neighborhood of Bel-Air. Playing on his rapper persona, and at times featuring his friend Jazzy Jeff, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air</em></span> was a huge success that ran for six seasons.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Meanwhile, Will and Jeff continued producing music, their 1991 album&nbsp;<em><u>Homebase</u></em>&nbsp;produced one of the all-time classic hip-hop singles, \"<em>Summertime</em>\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While still making <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air</em></span>, Smith began a second crossover into movies. After some smaller roles in feature films, he began to gain serious notice as an actor as the lead in the critically acclaimed film&nbsp;<em><u>Six Degrees of Separation</u></em>&nbsp;(1993).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Will Smith's first steps into superstardom came with his next film,&nbsp;<em><u>Bad Boys</u></em>&nbsp;(1995). The big-budget movie saw him team up with our brother, the legendary comic Martin Lawrence. Initially written for two white lead characters, the unexpected casting of two black leads proved an instant success and catapulted both their careers into Hollywood’s A-list.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Will Smith next took on the blockbuster sci-fi action film <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Independence Day</em></span> in 1996. A role that confirmed him as a major player in Hollywood and the go-to guy for summer blockbusters. He played a pilot leading the counterattack against invading alien forces, and his comedic talents effortlessly blended with his charisma on-screen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Smith fought aliens again in his next blockbuster film, <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Men in Black</em></span> (1997). Will Smith rapped the theme song, and its inclusion on his 1997 solo album,&nbsp;<em><u>Big Willie Style</u></em>, brought the multi-talented actor more success. Another blockbuster followed with the thriller&nbsp;<em><u>Enemy of the State</u></em>&nbsp;(1998.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2001 Will Smith portrayed our brother, the celebrated champion Muhammad Ali. In the film&nbsp;<em><u>Ali</u></em>, will Smith put in the performance of his life, training and disciplining himself to extraordinary lengths to do justice to the athleticism — and ego — of our brother. Critics recognized his efforts and Will’s performance was earned him his first Academy Award nomination.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Smith's smooth-talking charmer persona was put to use in the 2005 romantic comedy&nbsp;<em><u>Hitch</u></em>, and he followed it up with another critical and financial success,&nbsp;<em><u>The Pursuit of Happyness</u></em>&nbsp;(2006). Starring alongside his real-life son Jaden, Will Smith captivated audiences with the true-story of a single father who has to build a life from scratch in San Francisco. For his performance, he received his second Academy Award nomination.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2007, Will Smith starred in the international hit film&nbsp;<em><u>I Am Legend</u></em>, where he portrays an Army doctor who battles bloodthirsty zombies in post-apocalyptic New York City.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Will Smith stayed active throughout the late 2000s and early 2010s. In addition to starring in films, he parlayed his experience into production as well, producing numerous mainstream media projects under the <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Overbrook Films</span> banner.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2016, Smith starred in the DC Comics blockbuster hit&nbsp;<em><u>Suicide Squad</u></em>, which became his most successful film since 1996's <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Independence Day</em></span>. In February 2019, Smith announced that he would not be returning for the Suicide Squad sequel.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Around that time, he revealed that he was cast as the wisecracking Genie the live-action adaptation of Disney's&nbsp;<em><u>Aladdin</u></em>, which went on to top $1 billion at the global box office. He also opened 2020 with a third installment of the successful buddy-cop franchise&nbsp;<em><u>Bad Boys</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On his birthday, we have to give it up for the triple-threat. The man who achieved major mainstream success in three different entertainment fields: music, television, and movies. Our modern-day renaissance man of performance, our brilliant brother, The Fresh Prince, Mr. Will Smith.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-09-25 06:51:59","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"12021","featured_media_src_url":"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/WillSmith1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2286","post_author":"3","post_title":"Tyler Perry","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2290]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-1 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/TylerPerry3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2290\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/TylerPerry3.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2290\" class=\"wp-image-2290\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born September 13, 1969</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Playwright / Actor / Director / Producer / Screenwriter </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2287} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Tyler-Perry.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Born Emmitt Perry Jr. on this day September 13, 1969, in New Orleans, Louisiana. The man we now know as Tyler Perry had a difficult childhood. He suffered years of abuse at the hands of his father. He once described his father as a man \"<em>whose answer to everything was to beat it out of you</em>.\" Young Emmitt also had problems outside the home, as he later admitted he was sexually abused by four different adults.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At one point, Perry attempted suicide in an effort to escape his difficult situation. At 16, he changed his first name to Tyler to separate himself from his father. Perry dropped out of high school, but he eventually earned his GED. Trying to find his way professionally, he held a series of unfulfilling jobs before discovering his true passion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Watching an episode of Oprah Winfrey's talk show, Tyler was inspired by a comment on the program about how writing about difficult experiences could lead to personal breakthroughs. He started a series of letters to himself, which became the basis for the musical&nbsp;<em><u>I Know I've Been Changed</u></em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After saving up $12,000, Perry debuted the show — which he directed, produced and starred in — at an Atlanta theater in 1992. The musical's run lasted only one weekend and drew a measly 30 people to see the show.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Disappointed yet determined, Tyler Perry continued to work odd jobs while reworking the show. He staged the show in several other cities, but success still eluded him. Having spent all of his money, Tyler lived out of his car.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1998, Perry tried one more time to win over theater audiences. He rented out the House of Blues in Atlanta for another production of <em><u>I Know I've Been Changed</u></em>. Soon Perry was performing to sellout crowds and the musical was moved to a larger theater. After so many years of hard work, he had finally earned critical acclaim as well as commercial success.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":2291,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/TylerPerry4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-2291\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For his next project, Perry worked on an adaptation of a T. D. Jakes' book <em><u>Woman, Thou Art Loosed</u></em>, which proved to be quite popular. His next effort, however, brought to life his most famous character, <em>Madea</em>. The gun-toting, sharp-tongued grandma first appeared in his year 2000 play, <em><u>I Can Do Bad All by Myself</u></em>. Basing Madea on his mother and several other mature women in his life, Perry played the eccentric character himself wearing drag. She next appeared in <em><u>Diary of a Mad Black Woman</u></em> (2001).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Developing quite a following, the Madea character was featured in a number of plays. Perry toured extensively with his shows. According to his website, 35,000 people a week saw one of his shows in 2005.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That same year, Perry proved himself to be a box office powerhouse with the release of his debut film,&nbsp;<em><u>Diary of a Mad Black Woman</u></em>. Perry appeared as three different characters in the film, including the legendary Madea. Eventually grossing more than $50 million, the film's success showed Hollywood that there was a mainstream market for his audience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Perry's plays continued to make a successful leap to the big screen. He took on the leading role in&nbsp;<em><u>Madea's Family Reunion</u></em>&nbsp;(2006). He established his own studio in Atlanta that year, he launched his first television series,&nbsp;<em><u>House of Payne</u></em>, on the TBS network.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Back on the big screen, Perry continued making films about family, morals and overcoming adversity, such as&nbsp;<em><u>Daddy's Little Girls</u></em>&nbsp;,&nbsp;<em><u>Why Did I Get Married?</u></em>, and&nbsp;<em><u>Meet the Browns</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2009 Tyler Perry teamed up to co-produce&nbsp;<em><u>Precious</u></em>, a drama adapted from the novel&nbsp;<em><u>Push</u></em>&nbsp;by Sapphire. The film was nominated for an Academy Award. In 2010, Tyler Perry directed a film version of&nbsp;<em><u>For Colored Girls Who Have Considered Suicide When the Rainbow Is Enuf</u></em>, based on the famous 1975 play.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Recently, Tyler Perry continued to make successful films in the&nbsp;<em><u>Madea</u></em>&nbsp;franchise. Perry also launched several TV series during this period, many of them featured on the&nbsp;Oprah Winfrey Network&nbsp;(OWN). The most popular of them, being&nbsp;<em><u>The Haves and the Have Nots</u></em>. In 2011, Forbes listed him as the highest-paid man in entertainment, earning $130 million.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In October 2019 the entertainment mogul announced the grand opening of the $250 million Tyler Perry Studios on the site of a former 330-acre Confederate military base in Atlanta. The studio had already been in use while under construction, with features like&nbsp;<em><u>Black Panther</u></em>,&nbsp;<em><u>Coming 2 America</u></em>, and series like&nbsp;<em><u>The</u></em>&nbsp;<em>Walking Dead</em>&nbsp;filmed there.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adding to his already dynamic career, Perry wrote the 2006 best-selling book,&nbsp;<em><u>Don't Make a Black Woman Take Off Her Earrings: Madea's Uninhibited Commentaries on Love and Life</u></em>. The book went on to win two Quill Awards—Book of the Year and Best in Humor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tyler Perry was included in&nbsp;<em><u>Time</u>&nbsp;</em>magazine's “<em>100 Most Influential People of 2020</em>.” And on his birthday, we show our love to one of the hardest working men in showbusiness, our brother, the dynamic Mr. Tyler Perry.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-09-13 06:41:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"11445","featured_media_src_url":"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/TylerPerry1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2249","post_author":"3","post_title":"Dorothy Jean Dandridge","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2253,2252]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/DorothyDandridge1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2253\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/DorothyDandridge1.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2253\" class=\"wp-image-2253\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/DorothyDandridge2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2252\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/DorothyDandridge2.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2252\" class=\"wp-image-2252\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>November 9, 1922 – September 8, 1965</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Actress / Singer</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2250} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Dorothy-Dandridge.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dorothy Dandridge was born on November 9, 1922, in Cleveland, Ohio, the second of two daughters. Her mother was an aspiring entertainer and her father was a carpenter. Her mother created a song-and-dance act for her daughters. With that act, they would have some success, and despite their tender ages, they toured full-time throughout the Southern states during the 1920s, performing at venues for mostly black audiences.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1930, Dorothy’s mom moved to Hollywood, California, and the sisters continued to perform, known as “The Dandridge Sisters”. During the time, they would appear in short films and were booked to perform in high-profile nightclubs throughout the US like the Cotton Club and the Apollo Theater.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 1940s, Dorothy’s star really began to take off, as she made many appearances on stage and screen. A true entertainment pioneer, throughout her career she would become a black woman of several “firsts.”&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 1940s, she gained fame for her appearances in “soundies” which were the predecessors of modern-day music videos. These short 3-minute films were played on “movie jukeboxes,” which were extremely popular in those days.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1951, she graced the cover of Ebony magazine, for the controversy surrounding her acclaimed appearance as “<em>Queen Malendi</em>” in the Tarzan movies. In 1953, she landed the leading role in Broadway musical, <em><u>Carmen Jones,</u></em>which was one of the first major Hollywood movies that featured an all-black cast. Her performance in the film would garner her an Academy Award nomination for Best Actress, becoming the first black female to be so honored. Her appearance in the film left such an impact on viewers that she became known for being the first black sex-symbol in the US.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1955, she performed at the famed Empire Room, in the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in New York City, becoming the first black person to do so. The success of the event paved the way for other black entertainers to headline there.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1957, she would appear in the film <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>I</em></span><em><u>sland in the Sun</u></em>. This was notable because the film was the first contemporary Hollywood film to depict an interracial relationship. Despite the controversy, the film would go on to receive favorable reviews and strong box-office success.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Later in her life, Dorothy would be mired in a variety of lawsuits, financial troubles, and failed marriages. She would however continue acting and performing throughout the 50s and into the 60s.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our sister, Dorothy Jean Dandridge, made her transition on this day, September 8, 1965. Her cause of death was disputed by medical examiners and is still a mystery. In the 1980s, her legacy began to be celebrated. In 1984, she was also awarded a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame. In 1999, her life-story was adapted into a biopic produced by HBO Films, starring Halle Berry.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-09-08 06:49:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"9006","featured_media_src_url":"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/DorothyDandridge3.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"2231","post_author":"3","post_title":"Nina Mae McKinney","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[2235,2234]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/NinaMckinney1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2235\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/NinaMckinney1.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2235\" class=\"wp-image-2235\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/NinaMckinney2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"2234\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/NinaMckinney2.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=2234\" class=\"wp-image-2234\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>June 12, 1912 – May 3, 1967</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Actress</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":2232} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Nina-Mae-McKinney.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nina Mae McKinney was born on June 12, 1912 in the small town of Lancaster, South Carolina.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nina was raised by her aunt, because early in her life her parents moved to New York City for better work opportunities. As a child, she learned to ride a bike and perform stunts. She acted in school plays in Lancaster and taught herself to dance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With hopes of establishing an acting career, she left South Carolina and moved to New York City, where she also reunited with her parents. Her debut on Broadway was dancing in a chorus line of the hit musical Blackbirds of 1928. The show became one of the most successful shows on Broadway at the time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the impressionable age of sixteen, Nina Mae McKinney landed the leading role in the film “<em><u>Hallelujah!</u></em>” This is significant because, not only was it was the first ever all-black musical film, but the success of the film put a spotlight on Nina as the first black woman actor to receive mainstream Hollywood recognition.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After&nbsp;<em><u>Hallelujah!</u></em>, McKinney was the first black actor to sign a long-term contract with a major Hollywood studio. However, the studio seemed reluctant to star her in feature films. Work was hard to come by in Hollywood because not many movies were interracial, and it was difficult for blacks in show business to find enough work. Although the multi-talented McKinney was lauded for her strikingly beautiful looks, Hollywood was scared of her, and film production codes also prohibited suggestions of interracial relationships.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In December 1932, McKinney moved to Paris, where she performed as a cabaret entertainer. She found the European entertainment industry to be more accepting of her talent, and she toured and performed in numerous films throughout the 1930s. She returned to the United States after the German invasion of Poland in September 1939.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Upon her return to the USA, she would continue her acting career. She would earn starring roles in films aimed at black audiences, but because of racism, she would only be allowed to play stereotypical roles in Hollywood films. After World War II, she returned to Europe to live until 1960 when she returned to New York.On May 3, 1967, our sister Nina Mae McKinney died of a&nbsp;heart attack&nbsp;at the age of 54 in Manhattan, NYC. She was inducted into the Black Filmmakers Hall of Fame in 1978.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-09-05 06:15:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"8934","featured_media_src_url":"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/NinaMckinney3.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"1824","post_author":"3","post_title":"Diahann Carroll","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1827,1826]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/DiahannCarroll2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1827\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/DiahannCarroll2.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1827\" class=\"wp-image-1827\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/DiahannCarroll1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1826\" data-full-url=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/DiahannCarroll1.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1826\" class=\"wp-image-1826\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>July 17, 1935 – October 4, 2019</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Actress / Singer / Model&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":1825} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Diahann-Carroll.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She was born, Carol Diann Johnson, in the Bronx, New York City, on this day July 17, 1935.  Her father was a subway conductor, and her mom was a nurse. While she was still an infant, the family moved to Harlem. She attended a local high school with an arts program. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By the time she was 15, she was modeling for <em><u>Ebony</u></em> magazine, under the stage name “<em>Diahann Carroll</em>.” After graduating from high school, she attended New York University (NYU), where she majored in sociology, but she left before graduating to pursue a career in the entertainment industry. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She attended Manhattan's School of Performing Arts and worked as a nightclub singer and model before making her Broadway debut in&nbsp;<em><u>The House of Flowers</u></em>&nbsp;in 1954, for which she was nominated for a Tony Award for “<em>Best Featured Actress in a Musical</em>.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Diahann Carroll's film debut was a supporting role in <em><u>Carmen Jones</u></em> (1954), as a friend to the sultry lead character played by our sister, Dorothy Dandridge. A few years later, she played \"Clara\" in the film version of George Gershwin's <em><u>Porgy and Bess</u></em> (1959). </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1962, she starred with our brother Sidney Poitier, in the film&nbsp;<em><u>Paris Blues</u>.</em>&nbsp;That year Diahann also won a Tony Award for her role in the Broadway musical&nbsp;<em><u>No Strings</u>,</em>&nbsp;thereby becoming the first black actress to win the coveted award for theater.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Twelve years later, she was nominated for an Academy Award for “<em>Best Actress</em>” for her starring role alongside our brother, James Earl Jones in the film&nbsp;<em><u>Claudine</u></em>&nbsp;(1974).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Diahann Carroll is best known for her performance in the title role in the television series&nbsp;<em><u>Julia</u></em>&nbsp;(1968) which made her the first black actress to star in her own television series (who did not play a domestic worker). That role won her the Golden Globe Award for \"<em>Best Actress in A TV Series</em>\" and a nomination for an Emmy Award in 1969.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1984, Carroll joined the nighttime soap opera Dynasty as the jet set diva “Dominique Deveraux.” She thrived in her high-profile role on the show and Carroll remained on the cast until 1987. She received her third Emmy nomination in 1989 for her recurring role in the TV series&nbsp;<em><u>A Different World</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Diahann portrayed a memorable character in our brother, Robert Townsend’s classic film, <em><u>The Five Heartbeats</u></em> (1991). In 2006, Carroll appeared in the popular television medical drama <em><u>Grey's Anatomy</u></em>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2013, Carroll was present on stage for the 65th Primetime Emmy Awards, to briefly speak about being the first black person nominated for a Primetime Emmy Award.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our delightful superstar of the big and small screen, Diahann Carroll passed away on in October of 2019, in Los Angeles, California after a long battle with breast cancer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-07-17 06:34:43","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"7306","featured_media_src_url":"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/DiahannCarroll3.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"1624","post_author":"3","post_title":"Kendrick Lamar Duckworth","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1627,1628]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/KDot2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1627\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/KDot2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1627\" class=\"wp-image-1627\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/KDot3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1628\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/KDot3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1628\" class=\"wp-image-1628\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born June 17, 1987&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Recording Artist&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":1625} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/Kendrick-Lamar.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Kendrick Lamar Duckworth was born in Compton, California, on this day, June 17, 1987. His first name was given to him by his mother in honor of singer-songwriter Eddie Kendricks of The Temptations. His childhood was difficult as he grew up in relative poverty. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a child, Lamar attended local Compton schools. He is self-described as being quiet and shy in school, his mother even confirming that he was a \"loner\" until the age of seven.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1995, at the age of eight, Kendrick had an experience which would become a great foreshadowing into his bright future. He witnessed his idols Tupac Shakur and Dr. Dre filming the music video for their hit single \"<em>California Love</em>\", which proved to be an inspirational moment in his life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lamar's family was directly touched by the violence of the streets, yet he remained thoughtful and soft-spoken, ever the keen observer, even as a child. As a teenager, he attended Centennial High School in Compton, where he was a straight-A student.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 1980s and early 90s, Kendrick grew up around street activities, but he seemed more influenced than harmed by it. He was a good student who enjoyed writing stories, then poems, and then rap lyrics.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He adopted the moniker “<em>K-Dot</em>” and began performing his lyrics as a rapper. At age 16, in 2003, he circulated a mix tape called&nbsp;<em><u>Youngest HNIC</u></em>, which drew a lot of interest in his native Southern California and beyond.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The project was enough to get Kendrick a record deal with Top Dawg Entertainment, a respected California independent label and feeder to major labels. He went on to release several acclaimed mix tapes.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2010 Kendrick dropped “K-Dot” and began using his own first and middle name professionally. That same year, Kendrick Lamar released his first full-length independent album under Top Dawg Entertainment titled&nbsp;<em><u>Section.80</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lamar continued writing music and lyrics, and continued to tour and collaborate with more popular recorders of music. Dr. Dre, one of hip-hop's most respected and influential producers, took the young artist under his wing, becoming his mentor in both music and business.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As the buzz on Kendrick Lamar continued to build, Dr. Dre signed him to his independent record label, Aftermath Entertainment. Now the quiet, observant kid who made good grades in school was poised to become rap's newest superstar.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In October 2012, Kendrick's highly anticipated major-label debut album,&nbsp;<em><u>good kid, m.A.A.d city</u></em>, was released to wide acclaim. The rapper's emergence as a talent to watch, cleared the way for him to make major American television appearances while promoting the album.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Kendrick's appeal to the masses didn't stop there. The thought-provoking lyrics on his debut album caught the attention of hip-hop critics as well. Lamar remains popular for his sharp observations of street culture, often examining the psychology of the victims of crimes.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2015, Kendrick released his next album,<em><u>&nbsp;To Pimp a Butterfly</u></em>. Butterfly was another highly acclaimed outing known for its funk-laden mix of bravura, community politics and vulnerability. Lamar was nominated for a whopping 11 Grammys later that year.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The artist continued to wow fans with the April 2017 release of&nbsp;<em><u>DAMN.</u></em>, which featured such tracks as \"Humble\" and \"Loyalty.\" Along with achieving double-platinum status,&nbsp;<em><u>DAMN</u></em>. was named by BBC news as the critics' favorite album of 2017, based on the compilation of year-end polls.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Nominated for seven Grammys, his album&nbsp;<em><u>DAMN.</u></em>&nbsp;went on to sweep the rap categories, claiming Best Rap Album and Best Rap Song.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Kendrick Lamar made history in April 2018 when he won a Pulitzer Prize for music for DAMN., making him not only the first person to win a Pulitzer for a hip-hop album, but also the first artist to win the prize for music that isn't classical or jazz. The Pulitzer board called the album \"<em>a virtuosic song collection unified by its vernacular authenticity and rhythmic dynamism that offers affecting vignettes capturing the complexity of modern … life</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Happy Birthday K-Dot. Thank you for picking up the pen and allowing your creative expression to come alive. We salute our brother Kendrick Lamar, and continue to wish you the best in your journey!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-06-17 06:39:13","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"6506","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/KDot1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"1512","post_author":"3","post_title":"Morgan P. Freeman, Jr.","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1515,1517]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/MorganFreeman2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1515\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/MorganFreeman2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1515\" class=\"wp-image-1515\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/MorganFreeman4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1517\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/MorganFreeman4.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1517\" class=\"wp-image-1517\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born June 1, 1937</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Actor / Director / Narrator</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":1513} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/Morgan-Freeman.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Morgan Porterfield Freeman was born on this day, June 1, 1937, in Memphis, Tennessee. He was the youngest of five. His father was a barber and his mother, a schoolteacher.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a kid, Freeman spent a good portion of his time scraping together enough money to see movies. It was by chance that Freeman himself got into acting. He was in junior high school and, as punishment for pulling out a chair from underneath a girl he had a crush on, Freeman was ordered to participate in the school's drama competition. To his surprise, and probably school administrators, the 12-year-old proved to be an immediate natural on the stage, taking top honors in the program.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But while Freeman loved to act, flying — in particular the idea of being a fighter pilot—was in his heart of hearts. And so, upon graduating high school in 1955, Morgan turned down a partial drama scholarship and joined the U.S. Air Force. The military, though, proved to be much different than what he'd expected. Instead of darting around the skies, Morgan was relegated to on-the-ground activity as a mechanic and radar technician. He also realized that he didn't want to be shooting down other people.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1959, Freeman left the Air Force and tried his fortunes out West, moving to Hollywood to see if he could make it as an actor. It wasn't an easy life. He took acting classes and struggled to find work. In the early 1960s, he moved again, this time to New York City, where more petty day jobs and nighttime auditions followed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1967, Freeman's big career break came when he landed a part in an all-black Broadway production of&nbsp;<em><u>Hello, Dolly!</u></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some national exposure followed in 1971 when he started appearing regularly on&nbsp;<em><u>The Electric Company</u></em>, a public television-produced children's TV show that focused on teaching kids how to read.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But television proved to be a grueling and demanding life for Freeman. Despite some stage work, including a Tony-nominated performance in the late 1970s, Freeman couldn't seem to break into movies like he wanted. When&nbsp;<em><u>The Electric Company</u></em>&nbsp;was canceled in 1976, Freeman saw himself staring at a career that was far from grounded.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For much of the rest of the decade, Freeman took on roles that earned him some acclaim — but not the big, powerful jobs that would garner A-list attention.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1987, Freeman's fortunes changed when he was cast in the film&nbsp;<em><u>Street Smart</u></em>. The role proved to be huge success for Freeman, earning him an Oscar nomination for Best Supporting Actor. Two years later, Freeman earned more acclaim — a Golden Globe Award for Best Actor and a second Oscar nomination — as the kind-hearted but stubborn chauffeur in 1989's&nbsp;<em><u>Driving Miss Daisy</u></em>. That same year he also starred in the critically acclaimed film&nbsp;<em><u>Glory</u></em>, a drama about the first recognized black units in the Civil War. By the 1990s, Freeman was riding high in his career, starring in big budget films.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2005, Freeman won an Oscar for Best Supporting Actor in Clint Eastwood's&nbsp;<em><u>Million Dollar Baby</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the 2012 Golden Globes, Freeman received the Cecil B. DeMille Award for \"<em>Outstanding Contributions to the World of Entertainment</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Freeman's eloquent, distinctive voice has also made him a natural for narration. His voice can be heard on such memorable films as the Academy Award-winning documentary&nbsp;<em><u>March of the Penguins</u></em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2009, Freeman teamed up with Eastwood again, playing the role of South African President Nelson Mandela in&nbsp;<em><u>Invictus</u></em>&nbsp;— the role earned him an Oscar nod for Best Actor.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In September 2016, President Obama presented Morgan Freeman with a National Medal of Arts.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On his birthday, we salute one of the greatest actors of our generation, Mr. Morgan Freeman! Thank you for your valuable contributions to the culture.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-06-01 06:36:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"7575","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/MorganFreeman1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"1264","post_author":"3","post_title":"Percy R. Miller (Master P)","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1267,1266]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/MasterP2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1267\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/MasterP2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1267\" class=\"wp-image-1267\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/MasterP1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1266\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/MasterP1.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1266\" class=\"wp-image-1266\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Recording Artist / Producer / Entrepreneur&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born April 29, 1970</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":1265} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Master-P.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Percy Robert Miller was born on this day, April 29, 1970, in New Orleans, Louisiana. His parents divorced when he was very young, and Percy and his four siblings were raised by their father in New Orleans' Calliope Projects, a neighborhood infamous for its high crime rate.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He says that the turning point in his childhood came at age 16, when he saw a former resident of the Calliope Projects, who had left to become an insurance salesman, return to the neighborhood in a Mercedes-Benz.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Percy attended high school in New Orleans, starring as a point guard on the basketball team. After graduating in 1987, he briefly enrolled at the University of Houston to play basketball. However, he dropped out just months into his freshman year and transferred to Merritt Junior College in Oakland, California. He was studying business at Merritt when his grandfather passed away, and Miller received $10,000 as part of a settlement awarded his family due to the circumstances of the death. Armed with nothing but the settlement money and two years of business classes, Percy opened his own record store, No Limit Records, in nearby Richmond, California.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Miller used his record store to scope out sales trends in the hip-hop industry. After perceiving an unfulfilled demand for more hard-edged gangster rap music, he expanded No Limit into a record label and self-produced his own debut album, under the name Master P, called&nbsp;<em><u>Get Away Clean</u></em>, in 1991. Neither that album nor his second album sold well, and he decided to move No Limit Records back to his hometown of New Orleans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There Master P achieved his first real success with the 1994 album,&nbsp;<em><u>The Ghettos Tryin' to Kill Me</u></em>, and its 1995 follow-up,&nbsp;<em><u>99 Ways to Die</u></em>. Operating without a national distribution deal, Master P promoted the albums via word-of-mouth to independent music stores, managing to sell a quarter-million copies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Rappers had historically focused more on the artistic and glamorous side of hip hop music while paying very little attention to the business, investment and financial aspects. All that changed in 1996 when Master P signed a music distribution deal with Priority Records, one where No Limit Records would retain 100% ownership of their master recordings and keep 85% of their record's sales while giving Priority 15% in return for pressing and distribution which allows No Limit to profit from future sales such as catalogs and reissues. Master P went on to make hundreds of millions of dollars from this deal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He released his next album,&nbsp;<em><u>Ice Cream Man</u></em>, later that year and it peaked at No. 3 on the Billboard album charts. For the next several years, No Limit Records dominated the hip-hop industry, churning out a slew of hit records. By 1997, No Limit Records had expanded to include a bevy of prominent hip-hop stars. During its most productive years (1997-99), No Limit released 46 albums that frequently crowded the top of the Billboard charts.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Master P capitalized on the success of No Limit Records to expand into a host of other ventures. He explained his business model: \"<em>You spread out because you never know when it's going to end. Business is like a seesaw going up and down. When one goes down, I have the other one going up. You have to think like that if you want to survive</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Master P's first new enterprise was No Limit Films. In 1997, he personally funded and produced his first film&nbsp;<em><u>I'm Bout It</u></em>, earning an enormous profit when the film proved a surprise hit. This success landed No Limit Films a national distribution deal with Miramax. In another surprising extension of his entertainment empire, Master P founded No Limit Sports Management in 1997.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the same time as he entered the sports management business, Master P also plunged into the pro sports world as a basketball player. In 1998, he earned tryouts with the NBA's Charlotte Hornets and Toronto Raptors, greatly exceeding most expectations but ultimately failing to land on an NBA roster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite these setbacks, at the close of the 1990s Master P sat atop a self-made entertainment empire of grand scale. No Limit Records sold 75 million albums during the decade, and in 1998 Forbes magazine ranked Master P 10th on its list of highest-grossing entertainers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>More recently in June of 2020, Master P announced his own rice brand, Uncle P's Louisiana seasoned rice, which he hopes major retailers will begin selling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And in July of 2020, Master P released the <em><u>No Limit Chronicles</u></em>, a five-part BET docuseries on his New Orleans-based hip-hop label. The series shares stories of Master P’s career as a record executive and businessman, underscoring the unprecedented distribution deal with Priority Records that made No Limit Records a powerhouse record label.On his day, we salute the astute businessman, and entertainment mogul, Percy “Master P” Miller! He has shown us that there is <em>no limit</em> to our success.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-04-29 06:54:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"5066","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/MasterP3.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"1255","post_author":"3","post_title":"Edward K. \"Duke\" Ellington","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1262,1261]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/DukeEllington3-1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1262\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/DukeEllington3-1.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1262\" class=\"wp-image-1262\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/DukeEllington2-1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1261\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/DukeEllington2-1.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1261\" class=\"wp-image-1261\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>April 29, 1899 – May 24, 1974</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bandleader / Composer</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":1259} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/Duke-Ellington.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Edward Kennedy Ellington  was born on this day, April 29, 1899, in Washington, D.C.. Both his parents were pianists. When Edward was a child, his family showed racial pride and support in their home, as did many other families. Black people in D.C. worked to protect their children from the era's Jim Crow laws.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Daisy Ellington surrounded her son with dignified women to reinforce his manners and teach him elegance. His childhood friends noticed that his casual, offhand manner and dapper dress gave him the bearing of a young nobleman, so they began calling him \"Duke.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Duke Ellington started out as a sign painter. He built his music business through his day job: when a customer asked him to make a sign for a dance or party, he would ask if they had musical entertainment; if not, Ellington would offer to play for the occasion. Later, Duke Ellington moved out of his parents' home and bought his own as he became a successful pianist.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Duke Ellington was based in New York City from the mid-1920s onward and gained a national profile through his orchestra's appearances at the Cotton Club in Harlem. In the 1930s, his orchestra toured in Europe. Although widely considered to have been a pivotal figure in the history of jazz, Ellington embraced the phrase \"<em>beyond category</em>\" as a liberating principle and referred to his music as part of the more general category of American Music rather than to a musical genre such as jazz.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of the jazz musicians who were members of Ellington's orchestra are considered to be among the best players in the idiom. Ellington melded them into the best-known orchestral unit in the history of jazz. Some members stayed with the orchestra for several decades. A master at writing miniatures for the three-minute 78 rpm recording format, Ellington wrote more than one thousand compositions; his extensive body of work is the largest recorded personal jazz legacy, with many of his pieces having become standards.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ellington also recorded songs written by his bandsmen, for example Juan Tizol's \"<em>Caravan</em>\", and \"<em>Perdido</em>\", which brought a Spanish tinge to big band jazz. In the early 1940s, Ellington began a nearly thirty-year collaboration with composer-arranger-pianist Billy Strayhorn, whom he called his writing and arranging companion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With Strayhorn, he composed many extended compositions, or suites, as well as additional short pieces. Following an appearance at the Newport Jazz Festival, in July 1956, Ellington and his orchestra enjoyed a major revival and embarked on world tours. Ellington recorded for most American record companies of his era, performed in several films, scored several, and composed a handful of stage musicals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ellington was noted for his inventive use of the orchestra and for his eloquence and charisma. He was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom in 1969. Our brother, Duke Ellington made his transition on May 24, 1974, of complications from lung cancer and pneumonia, a few weeks after his 75th birthday.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His reputation continued to rise after his passing, and he was awarded a posthumous Pulitzer Prize Special Award for Music in 1999.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-04-29 06:18:20","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"8813","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/DukeEllington1-1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"1027","post_author":"3","post_title":"Pearl Mae Bailey","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[1030,1029]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/PearlB1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1030\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/PearlB1.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1030\" class=\"wp-image-1030\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/PearlB3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"1029\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/PearlB3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=1029\" class=\"wp-image-1029\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>March 29, 1918 – August 17, 1990</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Singer / Actress&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":1028} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Pearl-Bailey.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pearl Mae Bailey was born on this day, March 29, 1918, in Newport News, Virginia. She graduated from Booker T. Washington High School in nearby Norfolk, Virginia.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She made her stage-singing debut when she was 15 years old. Her brother was beginning his own career as a tap dancer, and suggested she enter an amateur contest at a theater in Philadelphia. Bailey won and was offered $35 a week to perform there for two weeks. She later won a similar competition at Harlem's famous Apollo Theater and decided to pursue a career in entertainment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pearl began by singing and dancing in Philadelphia's black nightclubs in the 1930s, and soon started performing in other parts of the East Coast. In 1941, during World War II, Bailey toured the country with the USO, performing for American troops. After the tour, she settled in New York. Her solo successes as a nightclub performer were followed by acts with such entertainers as our brothers, Cab Calloway and Duke Ellington.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1946, Pearl made her Broadway debut in <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>St. Louis Woman</em></span>. For her performance, she won an Award as the best Broadway newcomer. Bailey continued to tour and record albums in between her stage and screen performances. Early in the television medium, Bailey guest starred on CBS's TV Show <em><u>Wonderful Town</u></em>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1967, Pearl Bailey and Cab Calloway headlined an all-black cast version of&nbsp;<em><u>Hello, Dolly!</u></em>&nbsp;The touring version was so successful, a producer took it to Broadway where it played to sold-out houses and revitalized the long running musical. Bailey was given a special Tony Award for her role. The musical was also recorded to vinyl form and released as a rare album.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A passionate fan of the New York sports, Bailey sang the national anthem for the New York Mets at Shea Stadium prior to Game 5 of the 1969 World Series. She also sang the national anthem prior to Game 1 of the 1981 World Series for the New York Yankees at Yankee Stadium.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bailey hosted her own variety series on ABC,&nbsp;<em><u>The Pearl Bailey Show</u></em>&nbsp;in 1971 which featured many notable guests.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Following her 1971 television series, she provided voices for animations such as&nbsp;<em><u>Tubby the Tuba</u></em>&nbsp;(1976) and Disney's&nbsp;<em><u>The Fox and the Hound</u></em>&nbsp;(1981). She also won a Daytime Emmy award for her performance as a fairy godmother in an ABC Afterschool Special.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>She earned a degree in theology from Georgetown University in Washington, D.C., in 1985 at age 67.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Later in her career, Bailey was a fixture as a spokesperson in a series of Duncan Hines commercials. She also appeared in commercials for Jell-O, Westinghouse, and Paramount Chicken.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In her later years, Bailey wrote several books, including:&nbsp;<em><u>The Raw Pearl</u></em>&nbsp;(1968),&nbsp;<em><u>Talking to Myself</u></em>&nbsp;(1971), and&nbsp;<em><u>Pearl's Kitchen</u></em>&nbsp;(1973). In 1975 she was appointed special ambassador to the United Nations by President Gerald Ford. Her last book,&nbsp;<em><u>Between You and Me</u></em>&nbsp;(1989), details her experiences with higher education. In 1988, Pearl Bailey received the Presidential Medal of Freedom from Ronald Reagan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our talented and dynamic sister, Pearl Bailey, made her transition in Philadelphia in August of 1990. She had been dealing with complications from heart disease.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-03-29 05:05:46","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"4118","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/PearlB2.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"965","post_author":"3","post_title":"Jackie \"Moms\" Mabley","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[962,964]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Mabley1.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"962\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Mabley1.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=962\" class=\"wp-image-962\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Mabley2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"964\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Mabley2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=964\" class=\"wp-image-964\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>March 19, 1894 – May 23, 1975</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Comedian / Actress  </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":966} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Moms-Mabley.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Loretta Mary Aiken was born in North Carolina, on this day, March 19, in 1894. Her father owned and operated several successful businesses, while her mother kept house and took in boarders.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Her teenage years were tumultuous. Loretta had given birth to two children that had resulted from her being raped at age 11. At the age of 14, at the encouragement of her grandmother, Loretta ran away to Cleveland, Ohio, joining a traveling vaudeville-style minstrel show where she sang and entertained. In 1909, a year after leaving, both her parents were killed in tragic accidents.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Loretta quickly became one of the most successful entertainers of the “<em>Chitlin' Circuit</em>,” which was a name for black-owned clubs and performance halls that offered work to black entertainers. Though a product of segregation, these black clubs were safe and comfortable places for both black audiences and performers. While traveling with the show, Loretta became involved with fellow performer Jack Mabley. Though they never married, she began to use the name Jackie Mabley.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the arrival of the 1920s and the beginning of the Harlem Renaissance, Jackie found her way to New York where she performed her act in such famous venues as the Cotton Club and the Savoy Ballroom.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By the 1930s, the Depression slowed the entertainment business, and Jackie made ends meet by working at church socials and movie houses. By 1939, Jackie began to appear regularly at the Apollo Theater in Harlem, where over the next 35 years she would perform more than any other entertainer. Here she continued to develop her comedic act—the salty old lady with the stretchy face and gravelly voice. It was at the Apollo that she acquired the nickname \"<em>Moms</em>\" from her fellow performers who appreciated her nurturing sympathy.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Though Moms Mabley's act may seem stereotypical to some, it was really quite a clever show business ploy. While attractive young women, particularly black women, could show little in the way of intelligence or sexuality without condemnation, \"Moms\" was safe—because she was nonthreatening. From behind the shabby clothes and toothless grin, Mabley could offer sharp-witted insights and social commentary that would have been unacceptable from a more serious source.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Beloved by black audiences, Moms Mabley's whole persona was an \"inside\" joke, and she did not hesitate to focus her scathing humor on whites and their ill treatment of other races. She also demonstrated glimmers of an early feminism with her jokes about old men and their illusions of authority. One of her trademark jokes was, \"<em>Ain't nothing an old man can do for me, but bring me a message from a young man</em>.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 1960s, Mabley became known to a wider mainstream audience, playing Carnegie Hall in 1962, and making a number of mainstream TV appearances. Music became a regular part of her act and she had a song hit #35 on the Billboard Hot 100 on July of 1969, making Moms Mabley, who was 75 at the time, the oldest living person to have a U.S. Top 40 hit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Moms Mabley continued performing in the 1970s. While filming the 1974 film&nbsp;<em><u>Amazing Grace</u></em>, she suffered a heart attack. She returned to work three weeks later, after receiving a pacemaker.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our wise and hilarious sister, Jackie “Moms” Mabley made her transition in White Plains, New York, the following year, in May of 1975. She had been dealing with heart failure complications.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-03-19 06:00:05","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"966","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Mabley3.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"922","post_author":"3","post_title":"Quincy Delight Jones, Jr.","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[926,925]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/QJones2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"926\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/QJones2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=926\" class=\"wp-image-926\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/QJones3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"925\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/QJones3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=925\" class=\"wp-image-925\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born March 14, 1933</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Producer (Music / TV / Film) / Composer </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":928} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Quincy-Jones-.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Quincy Delight Jones Jr. was born on the South Side of Chicago on this day, March 14, in 1933. His mother was a bank officer and property manager, and his father was a semi-professional baseball player and carpenter. Young Quincy was introduced to music by his mother, who always sang religious songs, and by his next-door neighbor who played piano. Quincy would listen through the walls. The neighbor recalled that after hearing her play, she could not get him off her piano.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1943, Jones and his family moved to Washington State where his father got a wartime job at the Puget Sound Naval Shipyard. After the war, the family moved to Seattle, where Jones attended high school. In high school, he developed his skills as a trumpeter and arranger.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At age 14, Jones introduced himself to 16-year-old Ray Charles after watching him play at a local club. Quincy cited Ray as an early inspiration for his own music career, noting that, our brother, Ray Charles overcame a disability (blindness) to achieve his musical goals.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1951, Jones earned a scholarship to Seattle University. After one semester, Jones transferred to what is now the Berklee College of Music in Boston. He left his studies after receiving an offer to tour as a trumpeter, arranger, and pianist with our brother, the bandleader Lionel Hampton, and embarked on his professional career.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the road with Hampton, he displayed a gift for arranging songs. He moved to New York City, where he received commissions for writing song arrangements. In 1953, at the age of twenty, Jones traveled with Lionel Hampton for a European tour.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In early 1956, Quincy played trumpet in the studio band that supported then 21-year-old Elvis Presley in his first six television appearances. During the 1950s, Jones toured Europe with a number of jazz orchestras. He also studied music composition and theory in Paris, France.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1961, Quincy was promoted from Musical Director to Vice-President of Mercury Records, becoming the first black person to hold the position. During the same year, at the invitation of the director, he composed music for the movie&nbsp;<em><u>The Pawnbroker</u></em>&nbsp;(1964). It was the first of his nearly 40 major motion picture scores. Following the success of&nbsp;<em><u>The Pawnbroker</u></em>, Jones left Mercury and moved to Los Angeles. Throughout his career he would compose theatrical scores not only for movies, but for a variety of TV shows as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the 1960s, in addition to his solo work as a musician, Jones worked as an arranger for several notable pop, jazz, and R&amp;B singers.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1975, he founded Qwest Productions, for which he arranged and produced successful albums by Frank Sinatra and others. In 1978, he produced the soundtrack for&nbsp;<em><u>The Wiz</u></em>, the musical adaptation of&nbsp;<em><u>The Wizard of Oz</u></em>, which starred Michael Jackson and Diana Ross. In 1982, he produced our brother, Michael Jackson's,&nbsp;<em><u>Thriller</u></em>, which would go on to become the bestselling album in the history of the music industry.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Marking Jones's debut as a film producer,&nbsp;<em><u>The Color Purple</u></em>&nbsp;received 11 Oscar nominations that year. Additionally, through this picture, Quincy Jones is credited with introducing Whoopi Goldberg and Oprah Winfrey to film audiences around the world.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After the 1985 American Music Awards ceremony, Jones used his influence to draw most of the major American recording artists of the day into a studio to record the song \"<em>We Are the World</em>\" to raise money for the victims of famine in Ethiopia.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1990, Quincy Jones Productions joined with Time Warner to create Quincy Jones Entertainment. Through this production company, Jones produced the successful TV Shows:&nbsp;<em><u>The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air</u></em>,&nbsp;<em><u>In the House</u></em>,&nbsp;<em><u>The Jenny Jones Show</u></em>, and&nbsp;<em><u>MADTV</u></em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2001, Jones published his autobiography&nbsp;<em><u>Q: The Autobiography of Quincy Jones</u></em>. In 2018, he appears, as himself, in&nbsp;<em><u>Quincy</u></em>, a documentary about his life.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>His artistic accomplishments are too voluminous to state, but we will attempt to highlight a few:&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>His career spans over 70 years in the entertainment industry with a record 80 Grammy Award nominations, 28 Grammy Wins, and a Grammy Legend Award in 1992.</li><li>He was the first black person nominated for&nbsp;<em><u>Best Original Song</u></em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em><u>Best Original Score</u></em>&nbsp;categories at The Academy Awards&nbsp;</li><li>As an artist and producer, he has elevated the careers of numerous entertainers, which reads like a “Who’s Who” list of people, like the aforementioned Elvis Presley, Michael Jackson, Frank Sinatra, and Oprah Winfrey, but also The Beatles, Will Smith, Miles Davis, and many, many others.&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On his birthday, we honor the living legend of sound, the Beethoven of our era, the magnanimous musical genius, Mr. Quincy Delight Jones!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-03-14 06:00:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"3703","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/QJones1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"687","post_author":"3","post_title":"Andre Romelle Young","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[691,692]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/DrDre3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"691\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/DrDre3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=691\" class=\"wp-image-691\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/DrDre2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"692\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/DrDre2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=692\" class=\"wp-image-692\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born February 18, 1965</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Music Producer / Artist / Entrepreneur&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":689} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Dr.-Dre.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Andre Romelle Young (aka Dr. Dre) was born in Compton, California, on this day, February 18, in 1965. He was mostly raised by his grandmother. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a young man he was inspired by, our brother, Grandmaster Flash. Andre often attended a local nightclub to watch many DJs and rappers performing live. This particular nightclub had a back room with a small four-track studio. In was there where he recorded several demos. He later joined the musical group World Class Wreckin' Cru in 1984. The group would become stars of the electro-hop scene that dominated early 1980s West Coast hip hop.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1986, Dr. Dre met our brother, O'Shea Jackson, known to us all as Ice Cube, who collaborated with him to record songs for Ruthless Records, a hip hop record label run by our brother, Eric Wright or Eazy-E. With two other members, they formed the rap group NWA.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NWA’s style of hip-hop was different than most other forms that existed at the time. The group called it, “<em>reality rap</em>,” offering stark descriptions of violent, inner-city streets. The group's first full album&nbsp;<em><u>Straight Outta’ Compton</u></em>&nbsp;became a major success, despite an almost complete absence of radio airplay or major concert tours.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After Ice Cube left NWA in 1989 over financial disputes, Dr. Dre produced and performed for much of the group's second album, and he also produced tracks for a number of other acts on Ruthless Records.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After a dispute with Eazy-E, Dr. Dre left the group at the peak of its popularity in 1991 under the advice of Suge Knight, who positioned Dr. Dre as his flagship artist, and founded Death Row Records.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1992, Dr. Dre released his first single, the title track to the film&nbsp;<em><u>Deep Cover</u></em>, a collaboration with, our brother, Snoop Dogg. That same year, Dr. Dre's debut solo album&nbsp;<em><u>The Chronic</u></em>, was released under Death Row Records. Dr. Dre ushered in a new style of rap, both in terms of musical style and lyrical content, as well as introducing a number of new artists to the industry.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><u>The Chronic</u></em>&nbsp;became a cultural phenomenon, its G-funk sound dominated much of hip-hop music in the early 1990s. In 1993, the album was certified triple platinum, and Dr. Dre also won the Grammy Award for Best Rap Solo Performance.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1995, Death Row Records signed our brother, Tupac Shakur, and began to position him as their major star. However, in March of 1996 Dr. Dre left the label amidst a contract dispute and growing concerns that Suge Knight was financially dishonest. Later that year, he formed his own label, Aftermath Entertainment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During the 2000s, Dre focused on producing other artists, and occasionally contributing vocals. He signed Eminem in 1998 and 50 Cent in 2002, and co-produced their albums.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In July 2008, Dr. Dre released his first brand of headphones, Beats by Dr. Dre. In May 2014, technology giant Apple purchased the Beats brand for $3 billion, Apple's most expensive purchase by far. The deal made Dr. Dre “[the] richest man in hip hop.\"&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In June 2017, it was announced that Dr. Dre has committed $10 million to the construction of a performing arts center for the new&nbsp;Compton High School. The center will encompass numerous creative resources and a 1,200-seat theater.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Today, on his birthday, we salute our sonic genius, the producer, and amazing entrepreneur, Dr. Dre!&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-02-18 06:01:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"2762","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/DrDre1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"},{"ID":"672","post_author":"3","post_title":"Michael Jeffrey Jordan","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[675,674]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Jordan2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"675\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Jordan2.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=675\" class=\"wp-image-675\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Jordan3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"674\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Jordan3.png\" data-link=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=674\" class=\"wp-image-674\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born February 17, 1963&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Basketball Player / Business Mogul </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":678} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Michael-Jordan.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Michael Jeffrey Jordan was born in Brooklyn, New York City, on this day, February 17, 1963. His mother was a bank employee and his father was an equipment supervisor. When he was five years old, he moved with his family to Wilmington, North Carolina. Jordan attended a local high school where he highlighted his athletic career by playing basketball, baseball, and football. He tried out for the varsity basketball team during his sophomore year but, he was deemed too short to play at that level.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Motivated to prove his worth, Jordan became the star of his high school’s junior varsity team, and tallied several 40-point games. The following summer, he grew four inches and trained rigorously. Upon earning a spot on the varsity roster, Jordan averaged more than 25 points per game over his final two seasons of high school play.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jordan played college basketball for three seasons under coach Dean Smith with the North Carolina Tar Heels. As a freshman, he hit the game-winning jump shot in the 1982 NCAA Championship game.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jordan joined the Chicago Bulls in 1984 as the third overall draft pick, and quickly emerged as a league star, entertaining crowds with his prolific scoring while gaining a reputation as one of the game's best defensive players. His leaping ability, demonstrated by performing slam dunks from the free throw line in Slam Dunk Contests, earned him the nicknames \"Air Jordan\" and \"His Airness\".&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jordan won his first NBA championship with the Bulls in 1991, and followed that achievement with titles in 1992 and 1993. Jordan abruptly retired from basketball before the 1994 NBA season to play Minor League Baseball, but returned to the Bulls in March 1995 and led them to three more championships in 1996, 1997, and 1998, as well as a then-record 72 regular-season wins in the 1996 NBA season.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He retired for a second time in January 1999 but returned for two more NBA seasons from 2001 to 2003 as a member of the Washington Wizards.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jordan's individual accolades and accomplishments are astonishing, but among them include six NBA Finals Most Valuable Player (MVP) Awards, ten scoring titles, and five regular season MVP Awards. In 1999, he was named the 20th Century's greatest North American athlete by ESPN.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Jordan was twice inducted into the Basketball Hall of Fame, once in 2009 for his individual career and again in 2010 as part of the 1992 United States Men's Olympic basketball team (better known as \"The Dream Team\").&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the most effectively marketed athletes of his generation, Jordan is also known for his product endorsements. He fueled the success of Nike's Air Jordan sneakers, which were introduced in 1984 and remain popular today. He has an ownership stake in Jordan Brand, which is a multi-billion dollar subsidiary of Nike. Jordan also starred as himself in the 1996 film&nbsp;<em><u>Space Jam</u></em>&nbsp;and in the Emmy Award-winning miniseries&nbsp;<em><u>The Last Dance</u></em>&nbsp;(2020). Today, he is part-owner and head of basketball operations for the Charlotte Hornets, and NASCAR Cup Series Racing team. In 2014, Jordan became the first billionaire player in NBA history. At the time of this recording, with a net worth of over $2.1 billion, MJ is the fourth-richest black person in America.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We salute, our brother, one of the hardest working men in sports entertainment, out of North Carolina, His Airness, #23, Michael Jeffrey Jordan! Happy Birthday.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->","post_date":"2021-02-17 05:59:00","post_status":"publish","comment_count":"0","media_id":"2700","featured_media_src_url":"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/Jordan1.png","likes":"0","is_favourite":"0"}]

