/// ID : "4103"
/// post_author : "3"
/// post_title : "Douglas (Doug) Lee Williams"
/// post_excerpt : ""
/// post_content : "<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[4109,4106]} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams5.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"4109\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams5.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=4109\" class=\"wp-image-4109\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams8.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"4106\" data-full-url=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams8.png\" data-link=\"https://myblackhistorycalendar.com/?attachment_id=4106\" class=\"wp-image-4106\"/></figure></li></ul></figure>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Born August 9, 1955</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Football Player</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:audio {\"id\":4104} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-audio\"><audio controls src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/Doug-Williams.m4a\"></audio></figure>\n<!-- /wp:audio -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Late January is the time of year when in the United States, our version of football tends to take over the national consciousness. Around this time, the NFL playoffs and coming of the Super Bowl enter the forefront of our minds. Not so much in recent years, but in the late 80s there were very few black quarterbacks in the NFL, and there was an undercurrent sense that black athletes did not possess the leadership qualities and instincts that it took to be successful in that position. Well, on this day, January 31, 1988, all of that thinking changed, thanks to one man, our brother Doug Williams. This is his triumphant story of victory. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4110,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4110\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Douglas “Doug” Lee Williams attended Grambling State University where he played under our brother, head coach Eddie Robinson. As quarterback, Doug guided the Tigers to a 36–7 (.837 winning percentage) record as a four-year starter, and led the Tigers to three conference championships.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1977, Doug Williams led the NCAA in several passing categories, including total yards from scrimmage, passing yards, and touchdown passes. Doug Williams finished fourth in the Heisman Trophy voting. Doug Williams graduated from Grambling with a bachelor's degree in education, and he began work on his master's degree before the 1978 NFL Draft.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite the success that he enjoyed on the field, a coach from the Tampa Bay Buccaneers (HOF coach Joe Gibbs) was the only NFL coach that visited him for scouting purposes. Impressed by his poise, work ethic, and studious nature, the coach rated Williams as the best quarterback in the draft and recommended that the Buccaneers select Williams with their first-round draft choice.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4108,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams6.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4108\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Following the recommendation of Gibbs, Tampa Bay drafted Williams in the first round (17th overall) of the 1978 NFL Draft. Williams became the first black quarterback taken in the first round of an NFL draft. His first preseason pass drew a standing ovation from the Tampa Stadium crowd. In a 1979 game against the Chicago Bears, Doug Williams and our brother, Bears quarterback Vince Evans made history by making it the first NFL game ever to have a black starting quarterback on both teams.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Tampa Bay, which had won just two games in the first two years of the franchise, went to the playoffs three times in five seasons with Williams as starter and played in the 1979 NFC Championship game. During his time in Tampa Bay, Williams improved his completion percentage each season.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Williams was the only starting black quarterback in the NFL at that time. During his tenure with the Buccaneers, Williams was paid the lowest salary for a starting quarterback in the league, and less than the salary of 12 backups. After the 1982 season, Williams asked for a $600,000 contract. The Tampa Bay Bucs owner refused to budge from his initial offer despite the head coach’s endorsement.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4107,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams7.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4107\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Feeling disrespected by not being paid properly according to his merit, Doug Williams bolted to the upstart United States Football League's (USFL) Oklahoma Outlaws. The next season the Bucs went 2–14, and did not make the playoffs again until the 1997 season 14 years later. Over time, Tampa Bay’s willingness to let Doug Williams walk away over such a relatively small amount of money was seen as insensitive, especially as it came only months after Doug Williams’ wife passed away suddenly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1984, Williams led the Outlaws of the USFL in passing, however, after the USFL was shut down in 1986, Doug Williams returned to the NFL, joining the Washington Redskins. He was reunited with his former offensive coordinator, Joe Gibbs, who was now the team's head coach. Initially, Williams served as the backup for the starting quarterback, but after the starter became injured, Doug Williams stepped in and led the Redskins to an opening-day victory against the Philadelphia Eagles in the 1987 season.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4112,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4112\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Doug Williams would start three times in the 1987 regular season. While the subsequent two starts were losses, at the end of the season, when the Redskins had qualified for the playoffs, Williams was chosen as the starter. And on this day, January 31, 1988, before an international audience, he bravely led the team to Super Bowl XXII in which they routed John Elway and the Denver Broncos, becoming the first black quarterback to both play in and win a Super Bowl. He threw for a record (at the time) of 340 yards (and four touchdowns), and he was named the Most Valuable Player of the championship game.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4111,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams3-770x1024.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4111\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He suffered from injuries the following season and was outplayed by the bench player, who eventually won the starting job from Williams. Doug Williams would play one final season in 1989, as a backup.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Following his departure from the NFL, Williams worked on television in 1990 as a college football analyst for the Black Entertainment Television (BET).&nbsp;&nbsp;Despite enjoying the change of pace, Williams longed to return to football and when a high school head coaching position opened up in 1991 at a new high School in Louisiana, Doug Williams applied for the job and was hired for the position.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 1992, Williams was able to move on to coach to his former high school. Playing its home games on a field bearing his name, Doug Williams was able to lead the team to an undefeated regular season.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Williams moved to the collegiate coaching ranks in 1994, when he was hired as the running backs coach for the football team of the United States Naval Academy. His other jobs in football have also included work as an offensive coordinator and as a scout.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Doug Williams began his collegiate head coaching career at Morehouse College in 1997. He was named the head football coach at Grambling State University the following year, succeeding the legendary Eddie Robinson. He led the Tigers to three consecutive conference titles from 2000–2002, before leaving to rejoin the Tampa Bay Buccaneers as a personnel executive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":4105,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"http://myblackhistorycalendar.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/DougWilliams9.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-4105\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In 2009, Doug Williams and fellow Grambling State alumnus James Harris co-founded the Black College Football Hall of Fame. Each year, several notable football players from historically black colleges and universities are entered in its hall of fame at an induction ceremony in Atlanta.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->"
